{"id": "7686", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=7686", "title": "Mutamin", "text": "Mutamin is a gnome mage responsible for the large amount of basilisks in the &lt;a href=\"Mutamin%27s%20Garden\"&gt;Mutamin's Garden&lt;/a&gt; area east of &lt;a href=\"Temple\"&gt;Temple&lt;/a&gt;. The \"garden\" that he so jealously protects is a collection of petrified travelers and beasts \"sculpted\" by his basilisks.\nMutamin is found in the north-central portion of the area. After some quick banter, he'll become hostile. He first casts &lt;a href=\"Mirror%20Image\"&gt;Mirror Image&lt;/a&gt; on himself, and follows that up with &lt;a href=\"Horror\"&gt;Horror&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Melf%27s%20Acid%20Arrow\"&gt;Melf's Acid Arrow&lt;/a&gt;, so he needs to be killed or otherwise neutralized quickly.\nHe is accompanied by a &lt;a href=\"Basilisk\"&gt;Greater Basilisk&lt;/a&gt; just north-east of his position.\nDialog.\n\"Greetingssss, I am Mutamin. I hope you enjoy the artwork my pretty lizards have sculpted. They sculpt with their eyessss. They sculpt when nasty travelers come by, yesssss. I don't like nasty travelers. They should keep to the roads.\"\nRegardless of the option you choose, his reply is the same:"}
{"id": "4344", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4344", "title": "Mutamin's Garden", "text": "The Area East of Temple is also known as Mutamin's Garden.\nNotable encounters.\nEight &lt;a href=\"Lesser%20Basilisk\"&gt;Lesser Basilisk&lt;/a&gt;s and two &lt;a href=\"Greater%20Basilisk\"&gt;Greater Basilisk&lt;/a&gt;s, along with their \"sculptures,\" are found in two locations:\nAll of these basilisks are \"encounters\" in the sense that they are found in pre-determined numbers at pre-determined locations (although they carry random loot, usually \"mid-tier\" gems and jewelry but occasionally things like Level 3 wizard scrolls and Laeral's Tear Necklace) and they do not respawn.\nOther notable inhabitants:\nThere are several approaches to basilisk hunting:\nBring a few &lt;a href=\"Stone%20to%20Flesh\"&gt;Stone to Flesh&lt;/a&gt; scrolls, you may need them. Also, keep the &lt;a href=\"Protagonist\"&gt;Protagonist&lt;/a&gt; out of range of the basilisks, as he/she cannot be restored from petrification.\nEnemies.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Greater%20Basilisk\"&gt;Greater&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Lesser%20Basilisk\"&gt;Lesser Basilisk&lt;/a&gt;s in this area do not respawn.\nRespawning enemies: Black Bears, Brown Bears, Cave Bears, Flinds, Gibberlings, Gnolls, Gnoll Elite, Gnoll Slashers, Gnoll Veterans, Tasloi.\nMod content.\nIn the mod (EET) this area is named Sharp Teeth Plain."}
{"id": "49468", "revid": "46775035", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49468", "title": "Mutated Gibberling", "text": "Mutated Gibberlings are tougher than ordinary &lt;a href=\"gibberling\"&gt;gibberling&lt;/a&gt;s.\nGameplay.\nThe mutated variety has twice the &lt;a href=\"Hit%20Dice\"&gt;hit-dice&lt;/a&gt;, hit points, and &lt;a href=\"Attacks%20per%20round\"&gt;APR&lt;/a&gt;, and a lower &lt;a href=\"Armor%20Class\"&gt;armor class&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"THAC0\"&gt;THAC0&lt;/a&gt;. However, &lt;a href=\"Physical%20damage\"&gt;Damage per Hit&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Saving%20throw\"&gt;Saving Throws&lt;/a&gt; are the same. Oddly, they are only worth each when slain, whereas their lesser brethren are worth 35 each."}
{"id": "11141", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=11141", "title": "Mutated Spider", "text": "Mutated Spiders are a deadlier variety of &lt;a href=\"Small%20Spider\"&gt;Small Spider&lt;/a&gt; and are found in &lt;a href=\"Watcher%27s%20Keep\"&gt;Watcher's Keep&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Sendai%27s%20Enclave\"&gt;Sendai's Lair&lt;/a&gt;.\nMutated Spiders have a two &lt;a href=\"Hit%20point\"&gt;hit points&lt;/a&gt; less compared to small spiders but they have a permanent &lt;a href=\"Haste%20effect\"&gt;Normal Haste&lt;/a&gt; effect active and a higher number of attacks per turn. And unlike small spiders, they can deliver a lethal dose of &lt;a href=\"poison\"&gt;poison&lt;/a&gt; to their target creature upon a successful hit. Like all they are immune to &lt;a href=\"Web\"&gt;Web&lt;/a&gt;. \nThey are usually encountered in decent numbers and because of their increased movement speed, it is best to kill them quickly. Spells such as &lt;a href=\"Entangle\"&gt;Entangle&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Grease\"&gt;Grease&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Slow\"&gt;Slow&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Hold%20Animal\"&gt;Hold Animal&lt;/a&gt; or a &lt;a href=\"Wand%20of%20Paralyzation\"&gt;Wands of Paralyzation&lt;/a&gt; may help to slow them down.\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; assigns revised default AI scripts to guide their attack targeting and other combat behavior, which is more responsive to their enemies' protections and recognized vulnerabilities. They'll look for targets unprotected from &lt;a href=\"Poison\"&gt;Poison&lt;/a&gt; as a priority."}
{"id": "52147", "revid": "1966519", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=52147", "title": "My Missed Fortune", "text": "My Missed Fortune is a side quest in .\nAcquiring.\nAutomatically acquired once &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; has returned to the &lt;a href=\"Ducal%20Palace%20%28SoD%29\"&gt;Ducal Palace&lt;/a&gt; during the prologue.\nWalkthrough.\nSpeak with &lt;a href=\"Ophyllis\"&gt;Ophyllis&lt;/a&gt; in the basement of the Ducal Palace, discovering he has lost all your gold by wagering on dog races. Regardless of the conversation choices, he hurries off, promising to have your gold when you meet him outside the walls of the palace.\nHowever, once contact is again made, it is discovered that he has been brutally robbed, though he heard one of robbers mention they could return to the &lt;a href=\"Three%20Old%20Kegs%20%28SoD%29\"&gt;Three Old Kegs&lt;/a&gt; now. Traveling to said inn, a group consisting of &lt;a href=\"Berahli\"&gt;Berahli&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Hastus\"&gt;Hastus&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Ozil\"&gt;Ozil&lt;/a&gt;, and three &lt;a href=\"Refugee\"&gt;Refugee&lt;/a&gt;s can be found around a large meal. \nIf confronted, there are three possible outcomes:\nOphyllis will not be seen again until after the bridge encounter in the &lt;a href=\"Coast%20Way%20Crossing\"&gt;Coast Way Crossing&lt;/a&gt;, showing up once you return to camp. He continues to apologize and gives you a &lt;a href=\"Gold%20Bust\"&gt;Gold Bust&lt;/a&gt; as partial payment for your lost coins, then leaves.\nIn after the attack on the &lt;a href=\"Coalition%20Camp\"&gt;Coalition Camp&lt;/a&gt;, Ophyllis will be found at the entrance, fatally impaled with &lt;a href=\"Ophyllis%27s%20Short%20Sword\"&gt;Ophyllis's Short Sword&lt;/a&gt;, which he managed to gasp out was due to being waylaid by Crusaders, who took 's gold.\nDuring &lt;a href=\"Chapter%20Eleven%20%E2%80%93%20Dragonspear%20Castle%20Battle\"&gt;Chapter Eleven&lt;/a&gt;, a locked chest can be found at &lt;a href=\"Dragonspear%20Castle%20Keep%20First%20Floor\"&gt;Dragonspear Castle&lt;/a&gt; (in the southwest room) with gold and a letter from Ophyllis thanking you for your patience.\n\"To be continued...\""}
{"id": "31977", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=31977", "title": "My old friend Imoen pestered me today.", "text": "\"My old friend Imoen pestered me today\" is a &lt;a href=\"journal\"&gt;journal&lt;/a&gt; entry in \"&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;\".\nThis entry is not related to a &lt;a href=\"quest\"&gt;quest&lt;/a&gt;. It can be obtained during the &lt;a href=\"Prologue\"&gt;Prologue&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Candlekeep\"&gt;Candlekeep&lt;/a&gt; when trying to &lt;a href=\"find%20Gorion\"&gt;find Gorion&lt;/a&gt; and nearing the steps to the &lt;a href=\"Candlekeep%20Library\"&gt;Candlekeep Library&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;a href=\"Imoen\"&gt;Imoen&lt;/a&gt;, who takes a break from her chores here, addresses &lt;a href=\"Party\"&gt;her childhood friend(s)&lt;/a&gt; for a little chit-chat. Only choosing the first available response will add the entry.\n&lt;onlyinclude&gt;\n&lt;/onlyinclude&gt;\nNotes.\nThis has no effect on a second talk with her or &lt;a href=\"Chapter%20One\"&gt;later events&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "50291", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=50291", "title": "Myconid", "text": "Myconids are &lt;a href=\"Fungus\"&gt;fungoid&lt;/a&gt;, sentient creatures that are &lt;a href=\"Alignment\"&gt;lawful neutral&lt;/a&gt; aligned. They are most often found in caves or other subterranean locations, but they may appear above ground in rare circumstances, as exposure to direct sunlight will kill them within an hour. They have a somewhat humanoid appearance with a red-capped mushroom head and a yellowish-brown colored central stem with a pair of arm-like limbs protruding from below their caps and a pair of legs that extend from below the stump. In their natural setting, they may react with hostility if a stranger approaches. They use no weapons nor carry any treasure.\nGameplay.\nThe Myconid innately casts a single target &lt;a href=\"Confusion%20%28innate%29\"&gt;Confusion (innate)&lt;/a&gt; spell at the closest detected enemy and repeat this approximately every two rounds until they are unable to. See the link for details.\nIn melee, they also utilize the same attack &lt;a href=\"UMBER01.ITM\"&gt;weapon&lt;/a&gt; as the &lt;a href=\"Umber%20Hulk\"&gt;Umber Hulk&lt;/a&gt;, inflicting 3d4 crushing damage plus strength bonus. The attack is equivalent to a +3 enchanted item for the purpose of what it can strike. Myconid's can strike twice per round.\nBugs.\nIn the original Shadows of Amn and the Enhanced Edition, myconids are miss-classified by General/Type as . In the myconids are now properly classified as General/Type: plant.\nFor the sake of proper classification within this wiki and to follow the correct D&amp;D classification, myconids are classified using the Siege of Dragonspear classification. \nMod content.\nInstallation of the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; Mod makes some changes to this creature. They have an SCS script to help the creature behave more intelligently in combat situations, such as not targeting enemies protected from Confusion, or if already in a confused state, and going after weakened or injured enemies as a priority, not attacking creatures in melee with Fire Shield up and active and that sort of thing."}
{"id": "50246", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=50246", "title": "Myconid Area (Slum Sewers)", "text": "The Myconid Area is a cave or grotto connected to &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla's&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Sewers%20%28Slums%20District%29\"&gt;Sewers (Slums District)&lt;/a&gt;. A staircase leading up can connect you to the cave. When you enter, there is a Minotaur who appears to be in a struggle with two &lt;a href=\"Myconid\"&gt;Myconid&lt;/a&gt;'s and a &lt;a href=\"Myconid%20King\"&gt;Myconid King&lt;/a&gt;. Several dead adventurers are also present laying on the cave floor. The Myconids will be hostile to your entry.\nNotable Loot.\nNone\nMod content.\nInstallation of &lt;a href=\"The%20Minotaur%20and%20Lilacor\"&gt;The Minotaur and Lilacor&lt;/a&gt; Mod adds content to this area encounter, seeking to expound on the unexplained situation at hand."}
{"id": "39278", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=39278", "title": "Myconid Bloom-Sac", "text": "The Myconid Bloom-Sac is in the inventory of the &lt;a href=\"Myconid%20Elder\"&gt;Myconid Elder&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Underground%20River%20Entrance\"&gt;Underground River Entrance&lt;/a&gt;. The &lt;a href=\"Fungus\"&gt;Myconid&lt;/a&gt; will drop the item if killed. Alternatively, if &lt;a href=\"Jaheira\"&gt;Jaheira&lt;/a&gt; is in the party, she can translate. &lt;a href=\"Bellowgulp%20Bluefingers\"&gt;Bellowgulp Bluefingers&lt;/a&gt; can also appear and translate. Both translation interactions can result in an exchange for the bloom-sac. The item summons 1d4 &lt;a href=\"Red%20Myconid\"&gt;Red Myconid&lt;/a&gt;s. &lt;a href=\"Ferrusk\"&gt;Ferrusk&lt;/a&gt; can trade the bloom-sac for the &lt;a href=\"Slime%20Sickness%20Curative\"&gt;Slime Sickness Curative&lt;/a&gt;, which is needed for the &lt;a href=\"Slime%20Sickness\"&gt;Slime Sickness&lt;/a&gt; ."}
{"id": "42354", "revid": "55272672", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=42354", "title": "Myconid Cave", "text": "The Myconid Cave is an in \"\".\nIt is accessed by descending into a large crater on the surface, the result of a powerful mage battle on the &lt;a href=\"Goblin%20Waylay\"&gt;road above&lt;/a&gt;.\nLayout.\nAs above, humanoid corpses little the cave floor and three hostile &lt;a href=\"Myconid\"&gt;Red Myconids&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0and a &lt;a href=\"Shrieker\"&gt;Shrieker&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0immediately attack the player. On the ground is a body with several spell scrolls (inludes &lt;a href=\"Lower%20Resistance\"&gt;Lower resistance&lt;/a&gt; 5th level mage spell) and a &lt;a href=\"Letter%20%28Myconid%20Cave%29\"&gt;Letter&lt;/a&gt;.\nFurther in, a second group will attack, consisting of a four Red Myconids, a &lt;a href=\"Myconid\"&gt;Blue Myconid&lt;/a&gt;, and another Shrieker.\nIn the corner are two hostile &lt;a href=\"Boring%20Beetle\"&gt;Boring Beetle&lt;/a&gt;s chewing on a body with a spell scroll, &lt;a href=\"Elven%20Chain%20Mail\"&gt;Elven Chain Mail&lt;/a&gt;, and the longsword &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Breaker%20%2B2\"&gt;Spell Breaker +2&lt;/a&gt;. Also, right under the magical magic illuminating crystal where the aforementioned body is, there is a hidden &lt;a href=\"Star%20Sapphire\"&gt;Star sapphire&lt;/a&gt; gem under a rock."}
{"id": "50292", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=50292", "title": "Myconid King", "text": "A Myconid King is a moderately improved version of the generally subterranean and intelligent &lt;a href=\"Myconid\"&gt;Myconid&lt;/a&gt;. They differ in appearance from a Myconid by having a blue-capped mushroom head and a bluish-grey coloration to the central stem and its appendages. They have a higher &lt;a href=\"Hit%20point\"&gt;hit point&lt;/a&gt; (50) and &lt;a href=\"XP\"&gt;XP&lt;/a&gt; (1200) total, an &lt;a href=\"Armor%20Class\"&gt;Armor Class&lt;/a&gt; of 2, and a &lt;a href=\"THAC0\"&gt;THAC0&lt;/a&gt; of 9. They use no weapons nor carry any treasure.\nGameplay.\nThe Myconid King innately casts a single target &lt;a href=\"Confusion%20%28innate%29\"&gt;Confusion (innate)&lt;/a&gt; spell at the closest detected enemy and repeat this approximately every two rounds until they are unable to. See the link for details.\nIn melee, they also utilize the same attack &lt;a href=\"UMBER01.ITM\"&gt;weapon&lt;/a&gt; as the &lt;a href=\"Umber%20Hulk\"&gt;Umber Hulk&lt;/a&gt;, inflicting 3d4 crushing damage plus strength bonus. The attack is equivalent to a +3 enchanted item for the purpose of what it can strike. The Myconid King can strike thrice per round.\nBugs.\nIn the original Shadows of Amn and the Enhanced Edition, myconids are miss-classified by General/Type as . In the myconids are now properly classified as General/Type: plant.\nFor the sake of proper classification within this wiki and to follow the correct D&amp;D classification, myconids are classified using the Siege of Dragonspear classification. \nMod content.\nInstallation of the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; Mod makes some changes to this creature. They have an SCS script to help the creature behave more intelligently in combat situations, such as not targeting enemies protected from Confusion, or if already in a confused state, and going after weakened or injured enemies as a priority, not attacking creatures in melee with Fire Shield up and active and that sort of thing."}
{"id": "51331", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51331", "title": "Myconid Room (Spellhold Test)", "text": "This area is technically part of &lt;a href=\"Spellhold\"&gt;Spellhold&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe party is transported to this area, to face a hostile group of creatures in battle, for the purpose of testing the resolve, clarity and inner workings of the party's mind. If the creatures are defeated the party will eventually be transported back to another examination chamber, only to be presented with further test questions. This is part of the &lt;a href=\"Escaping%20the%20asylum\"&gt;Escaping the asylum&lt;/a&gt; quest. \nGameplay.\nThe area will be a location that the party is transferred to by the &lt;a href=\"Apparition%20%28Spellhold%29\"&gt;Apparition&lt;/a&gt;, depending on how they replied to statements and questions in the &lt;a href=\"Kobold%20Room%20%28Spellhold%20Test%29\"&gt;Kobold Room (Spellhold Test)&lt;/a&gt; and possibly other tests administered by the Apparition in ither areas. \nAs soon as the party arrives in a cloud animation, the various creatures will attack detected party members. Innate spells will be launched by the mephits, and &lt;a href=\"Confusion%20%28innate%29\"&gt;Confusion (innate)&lt;/a&gt; from the myconids. The Greater Otyugh will start flailing its diseased tentacles in melee range.\nOnce the hostile beings are dispatched, another appearance of the Apparition takes place. He initiates dialogue and says:\nThe party is presented with a menu of dialogue reply options:\nThe party can refuse to answer the riddle and say \"Do not taunt me with nonsense! I will answer such insults with violence!\" - The Apparition responds: \"Hostility is dangerous in the face of the confused or irrational. You will receive a proper response, and your path grows harder.\"\nIf the party selects the correct answer to the riddle, the Apparition remarks:\nIf the party gives the incorrect answer to the riddle, the Apparition says:\nIf the party selects \"\"What is this? I do not understand your question.\" the Apparition replies: \n\"I refuse to answer your questions. You have no business knowing my mind.\". - The Apparition replies: \"I offer civilized discourse, and you counter with obstinance. Unfortunate. Your path is the hard one.\"\" - Transported to &lt;a href=\"Cave%20%28Spellhold%20Test%29\"&gt;Cave (Spellhold Test)&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br&gt; \n\"\"A primitive place, of no use to me. I would spend no more time here than I must.\" - The Apparition replies: \"Far too dismissive. You show inflexibility. Not desirable. The path will be harder still.\"\" - Transported to &lt;a href=\"Cave%20%28Spellhold%20Test%29\"&gt;Cave (Spellhold Test)&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br&gt;\n\"\"The land around this place would be fertile. It is not to be discounted.\" - The Apparition replies: \"You see a wider part of the picture. Such focus is good. Perhaps you are not lost after all. The path grows easier.\"\" - Transported to &lt;a href=\"Crushing%20Trap%20Room%20%28Spellhold%20Test%29\"&gt;Crushing Trap Room (Spellhold Test)&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;br&gt;\n\"\"It smells. What else would you have me make note of?\" - The Apparition replies: \"Nothing more than you would see. Such a narrow view is not good. You could be prone to fixation. The path grows harder.\"\" - Transported to &lt;a href=\"Cave%20%28Spellhold%20Test%29\"&gt;Cave (Spellhold Test)&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br&gt;\n\"\"A useless mire. Fill it in that it might be better appreciated.\" - The Apparition replies: \"Dismissive, but proactive. I will allow the answer, though my judgment is subjective. The path is a little easier.\"\" - Transported to &lt;a href=\"Crushing%20Trap%20Room%20%28Spellhold%20Test%29\"&gt;Crushing Trap Room (Spellhold Test)&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br&gt;\nIf &lt;a href=\"Cernd\"&gt;Cernd&lt;/a&gt; is in the party, the party won't even have an opportunity to select any desired answers. When the main question is asked \"What springs from this muck to your mind?\" Cernd replies \"If I might, it is the most basic of land\", the Apparition asks \"Is it? \" - Cernd explains, \"Within are stagnant smells and shades, but all around would bloom. A mire is useful in the proper place. &lt;CHARNAME&gt; would voice this better, of that, I'm sure.\" The apparition will respond:\nContainers.\nNone"}
