{"id": "46581", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=46581", "title": "Nadine's Home", "text": "Nadine's Home is the home of the halfling &lt;a href=\"Nadine\"&gt;Nadine&lt;/a&gt; and is located between two &lt;a href=\"Generic%20homes%20%28central%20Baldur%27s%20Gate%29\"&gt;generic houses&lt;/a&gt; (one to its right and the other one behind it) in the district of &lt;a href=\"Central%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;Central Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;. It faces the inner wall of the city. The front door is locked with a DC of 30.\nNadine can be found standing in the foyer when you enter the ground floor. The barrel in the kitchen contains a &lt;a href=\"Greenstone%20Ring\"&gt;Greenstone Ring&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe second floor is populated at night by a pair of sleeping men and women. In the smaller bedroom, the nightstand between the two beds contains 14 and the one in the corner contains 6 and a &lt;a href=\"Dagger\"&gt;Dagger&lt;/a&gt;. In the bigger bedroom, the nightstand to the right contains a &lt;a href=\"Sunstone%20Gem\"&gt;Sunstone Gem&lt;/a&gt; and the one to the left is empty. The chest of drawers contains 8 and the bookshelf has a copy of the &lt;a href=\"History%20of%20the%20North%20IX\"&gt;History of the North IX&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "11324", "revid": "53053884", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=11324", "title": "Nadine and Euric", "text": "This quest is obtained by talking to &lt;a href=\"Nadine\"&gt;Nadine&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Nadine%27s%20Home\"&gt;her house&lt;/a&gt; east of the fair in\u00a0&lt;a href=\"central%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;central Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;. She will ask Gorion's Ward to deliver an\u00a0&lt;a href=\"The%20Protector\"&gt;amulet&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0to her son\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Euric\"&gt;Euric&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0who has run away. Euric can be found in an &lt;a href=\"Generic%20Tavern%20and%20Inn%20%28Baldur%27s%20Gate%29%23AR1306\"&gt;unnamed inn&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"southeast%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;southeast Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;. If you give him the amulet from his mother he will admit that he ran away from home, but he will also add that he doesn't want to return yet. After that, return to Nadine to claim your reward."}
{"id": "4821", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4821", "title": "Nahal's Reckless Dweomer", "text": "Nahal's Reckless Dweomer is one of the three spells exclusive to the &lt;a href=\"Wild%20Mage\"&gt;Wild Mage&lt;/a&gt;.\u00a0 It must be placed in a level 1 spell slot before it can be used. Though called a spell, it does not have its own casting time, nor does it have casting delay.\u00a0 All that it does is\u00a0simply let Wild Mages use the level 1 spell slot to cast\u00a0any of their other known spells (Note: sequencer/trigger and contingency\u00a0spells cannot be cast this way in the Enhanced Edition).\u00a0 If two or more level 1 spell slots are filled with this\u00a0spell, as soon as one slot is used to cast one\u00a0spell, another slot can be activated\u00a0to cast another spell, as if the caster were constantly under the effect of &lt;a href=\"Improved%20Alacrity\"&gt;Improved Alacrity&lt;/a&gt;.\nThis spell\u00a0is the ultimate reason why lower-level Wild Mages can be very risky to play, and\u00a0higher-level Wild Mages can be extremely\u00a0powerful.\nThere are no scrolls for this spell in the game.\nGameplay.\nThe wild mage casts this spell on self and is instantly activated.\nThe caster now selects any spell known to the mage (it doesn't even have to be memorized, just in the spell book).\nThe dweomer causes a &lt;a href=\"Wild%20Surge\"&gt;Wild Surge&lt;/a&gt; to occur which will randomly affect the known spell as determined by the random probability roll and influenced in the mage's favor by their experience level and any chaos shield modifiers.\nAs the wild mage advances in experience, the results of the wild surges get more likely to produce the desired spell effect and less likely to result in some manner of disaster.\nDweomering sequencers and contingencies in the original game.\n A sequencer or contingency won't surge. But the next spell you cast will, 100%. This is a so-called postponed surge. You need to burn it with a dummy spell. Do not forget to do that.\nPostponed surges are\u00a0cumulative. If you dweomer minor sequencer, contingency, and then spell trigger, none of them will surge, but then the next\u00a03\u00a0spells will surge.\nTrivia.\nThe Advanced Dungeons and Dragons 2nd Edition Wild Mage spell \"Nahal's Reckless Dweomer \"differs from the BG game's implementation, as well as the &lt;a href=\"https%3A//adnd2e.fandom.com/wiki/Wild_Magic_Tables_%28TOM%29%23Table_2%3A_Wild_Surge_Results\"&gt;Wild Surge Table Results&lt;/a&gt;. Additionally, the chance of failure using this spell is much greater in the Pen and Paper game than the Bioware video game version - showing that this spell was meant to be a last-resort action, not a planned regular use spell. See the External links for further reading.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has changed this arcane spell, changing its effects, and school. See below for description:\nNahal\u2019s Reckless Dweomer\nLevel: 1\nSchool: None\nRange: Personal\nDuration: Special\nCasting Time: 1\nArea of Effect: Special\nSaving Throw: Special\nThis spell is the wild mage\u2019s ultimate last-resort spell. When cast, the mage releases a sudden flood of wild magical energy in the hope of seizing and shaping that energy into a desired spell effect. The attempt usually fails, but something almost always occurs in the process.\nTo use Reckless Dweomer, simply cast it and then choose from your list of known spells. A burst of magical energy is released, which the wild mage tries to manipulate into the desired form. The actual effect of the spell is determined randomly by a dice roll on the Wild Surge Table (found in your manual).\nBecause the release of energy is planned by the mage, his level is added to the dice roll. If the result indicates success, the mage has shaped the magical energy into the desired effect. More often than not, the effect is completely unexpected. The result may be beneficial to the mage, or it may be completely disastrous; this is the risk the mage takes in casting Nahal\u2019s Reckless Dweomer."}
