{"id": "11408", "revid": "6896023", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=11408", "title": "Neutralise Poison", "text": ""}
{"id": "5102", "revid": "49127847", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5102", "title": "Neutralize Poison", "text": "Neutralize Poison is a 4th level &lt;a href=\"priest%20spell\"&gt;priest spell&lt;/a&gt;. It heals the target for 10 &lt;a href=\"Hit%20point\"&gt;HP&lt;/a&gt; and removes the following status effects: &lt;a href=\"Poison\"&gt;Poison&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Disease\"&gt;Disease&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Deafness%20effect\"&gt;Deafness&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Blinded\"&gt;Blindness&lt;/a&gt;.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has changed this Divine spell, revising its effects, duration and description. See below:\nNeutralize Poison\nLevel: 4\nSchool: Necromancy\nSphere: Healing\nRange: Touch\nDuration: 1 turn/level\nCasting Time: 1\nArea of Effect: 1 creature\nSaving Throw: None\nThis spell removes all toxins from the body, both natural and magical in nature. When this spell is cast upon a poisoned individual, it immediately neutralizes any poison. In addition, for the duration of the spell, the recipient is immune to any poison it is exposed to, and spells like Poison and Cloudkill won\u2019t affect the protected creature."}
{"id": "45196", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=45196", "title": "Nevaziah", "text": "Nevaziah is a &lt;a href=\"Lich\"&gt;Lich&lt;/a&gt; hiding in the &lt;a href=\"Southern%20Dungeons\"&gt;Southern Dungeons&lt;/a&gt; below the &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Graveyard\"&gt;Athkatla Graveyard&lt;/a&gt;. It appears during &lt;a href=\"Find%20the%20Nether%20Scroll%20for%20Edwin\"&gt;Find the Nether Scroll for Edwin&lt;/a&gt; quest. At first contact with the party the lich is neutral but becomes hostile when &lt;a href=\"Edwin\"&gt;Edwin&lt;/a&gt; insists on demanding the Nether Scroll from him. Note that this scroll has no actual object in the game and isn't an \"item\" that can be placed into an inventory and carried or moved around.\nGameplay.\nThis creature is reduced in spell casting potential, as the Lich will not utilize spells greater than level 5. Nevaziah has unique physical damage resistances and is extra vulnerable to fire damage. The Lich also cannot see through Invisibility. \nIn terms of the creature's immunities and general abilities, have a look on the &lt;a href=\"Lich\"&gt;Lich&lt;/a&gt; article for a run down.\nUpon hostilities the creature may initially, if not disrupted, turn invisible with a &lt;a href=\"Shadow%20Door\"&gt;Shadow Door&lt;/a&gt;. It may also attempt a &lt;a href=\"Mirror%20Image\"&gt;Mirror Image&lt;/a&gt;. If it can, it will cast offensive spells such as &lt;a href=\"Fireball\"&gt;Fireball&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Cone%20of%20Cold\"&gt;Cone of Cold&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Lightning%20Bolt\"&gt;Lightning Bolt&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Agannazar%27s%20Scorcher\"&gt;Agannazar's Scorcher&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Magic%20Missile\"&gt;Magic Missile&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Stinking%20Cloud\"&gt;Stinking Cloud&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Remove%20Magic\"&gt;Remove Magic&lt;/a&gt;. That is all it has in its script arsenal, aside from an &lt;a href=\"Animate%20Dead%20%28wizard%29\"&gt;Animate Dead (wizard)&lt;/a&gt; and a &lt;a href=\"Monster%20Summoning%20III\"&gt;Monster Summoning III&lt;/a&gt; spell.\nIf Edwin is kept far enough away from the Lich (so as not to trigger Edwin's dialogue), then you can attack Nevaziah in a surprise assault and get the drop on the creature. To get the Nether Scroll, you must defeat the creature by violence. Once the creature is destroyed, then Edwin's dialogue should continue regarding the Scroll and keep the quest moving forward.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod revises Nevaziah to a level 14 Necromancer. In terms of spell selection and the \"Smarter Mage\" AI. SCS does in fact allow up to level 7 spell casts appropriate to a level 14 Necromancer. As is normal for SCS, an opening uninterruptible contingency is launched to raise some protective buffs. In the case of this lich, if a party member is under invisibility the lich will know someone approaching within range is invisible and cast a &lt;a href=\"Oracle\"&gt;Oracle&lt;/a&gt; spell and may say \"\"Strange... let's see what a little divination will show\", or \"Come out, spy... I can sense your presence\"\".\nIf made hostile, the lich will launch its precast buff contingency consisting of &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Immunity\"&gt;Spell Immunity&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Shield%20%28spell%29\"&gt;Shield (spell)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spirit%20Armor\"&gt;Spirit Armor&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Stoneskin\"&gt;Stoneskin&lt;/a&gt;. It will attempt a &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Magical%20Weapons\"&gt;Protection From Magical Weapons&lt;/a&gt; cast afterwards, as well as the SCS lich innate ability \"Fear Aura\", which tics every two rounds continuously. Now that its buffs are up, if the lich is not yet dead or disabled it will go on the offensive. The script has a large variable response based on the target vulnerability assessment. The choice of spells is wide. A &lt;a href=\"Remove%20Magic\"&gt;Remove Magic&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Breach\"&gt;Breach&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Greater%20Malison\"&gt;Greater Malison&lt;/a&gt; may be cast to weaken a target. A &lt;a href=\"Teleport%20Field\"&gt;Teleport Field&lt;/a&gt; is usual to break up the party's melee assault. \nA &lt;a href=\"Death%20Spell\"&gt;Death Spell&lt;/a&gt; is scripted to banish summoned party creatures will occur. The Lich will also summon a &lt;a href=\"Nabassu\"&gt;Nabassu&lt;/a&gt;, or &lt;a href=\"Shadow\"&gt;Shadow&lt;/a&gt;s. It has a high probability of casting &lt;a href=\"Cloudkill\"&gt;Cloudkill&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Finger%20of%20Death%20%28wizard%29\"&gt;Finger of Death (wizard)&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Disintegrate\"&gt;Disintegrate&lt;/a&gt;. If a party member is up close in melee with the Lich, it will attempt a &lt;a href=\"Vampiric%20Touch\"&gt;Vampiric Touch&lt;/a&gt; spell. All in all, except a much tougher encounter than the unmodified game.\nWith the &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod installed (which works with SCS), the lich will have the SR spell versions. For example, in its opening contingency it will have a \"\"Dispel Shield\" instead of Spell Immunity Abjuration. Instead of summoning a Nabassu, SR replaces that with a gated \"Death Knight\"\"."}
{"id": "15003", "revid": "49127847", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=15003", "title": "Neverwinter Nights", "text": "Neverwinter Nights is the name of two seperate game series, the first one by &lt;a href=\"https%3A//de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stormfront_Studios\"&gt;Stormfront Studios&lt;/a&gt; and the latter one by &lt;a href=\"BioWare\"&gt;BioWare&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"https%3A//de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Obsidian_Entertainment\"&gt;Obsidian Entertainment&lt;/a&gt;.\nNeverwinter Nights (1991).\nThe first \"Neverwinter Nights\" game was released in 1991 and is widely regarded as the first ever MMORPG and one of the so called &lt;a href=\"http%3A//goldbox.wikia.com/wiki/Gold_Box_Wiki\"&gt;Gold Box&lt;/a&gt; games.\nNeverwinter Nights (2002).\nThe first\u00a0\"Neverwinter Nights\"\u00a0in this series was developed by BioWare and released on June 18, 2002.\u00a0\"Neverwinter Nights 2\"\u00a0on the other hand was developed by Obsidian Entertainment and released on October 31, 2006.\nUnlike \"Baldur's Gate\", this series focuses much more on combat and multiplayer and comes with an extensive editor which allows players to create their own modules. Also unlike BG, it is based on \"Dungeons &amp; Dragons v3.5\"\u00a0rules instead of \"Advanced Dungeons &amp; Dragons 2nd Edition\".\nThere are two main games in the series, both of which received a number of expansion packs:\nSetting.\nLike \"Baldur's Gate\", \"Neverwinter Nights\" is set in the &lt;a href=\"Forgotten%20Realms\"&gt;Forgotten Realms&lt;/a&gt; and mainly focuses on the eponymous city of &lt;a href=\"http%3A//forgottenrealms.wikia.com/wiki/Neverwinter\"&gt;Neverwinter&lt;/a&gt;, which lies at the northern half of the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast\"&gt;Sword Coast&lt;/a&gt; but takes the player to all sorts of places, such as &lt;a href=\"http%3A//forgottenrealms.wikia.com/wiki/Rashemen\"&gt;Rashemen&lt;/a&gt;, the &lt;a href=\"Underdark\"&gt;Underdark&lt;/a&gt; and even &lt;a href=\"http%3A//forgottenrealms.wikia.com/wiki/Maztica\"&gt;Maztica&lt;/a&gt;.\nCross-references between Games.\nIn addition to general cross-references based on the setting, there exist a number of game-specific references.\nMod content.\nDeveloped over the course of 5 years by Russian modder AGKanevchev (with help from paladin84 in relation to weidu and bug-fixing), the mod &lt;a href=\"https%3A//forums.beamdog.com/discussion/88115/mod-neverwinter-for-baldurs-gate/p1\"&gt;Neverwinter for Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt; recreates Neverwinter Nights 1 (the base game, without expansions) in the BG2(EE) engine through clever use of Infinity Engine games and Pillars of Eternity 1+2 art assets. Some creative liberties were taken, however, in terms of gameplay: the mod completely rebalances the adventure to fit much higher level combat from the start (in fact, the NPC to start the mod will only spawn once Gorion's Ward reaches 1350000 XP) and, of course, it utilizes BG2(EE)'s version of the 2e AD&amp;D ruleset instead of the 3e ruleset."}
{"id": "7494", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=7494", "title": "Neville", "text": "Neville is a bandit who will try to ambush &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; and party in the &lt;a href=\"Bear%20River\"&gt;Bear River&lt;/a&gt; area north of the &lt;a href=\"Gnoll%20Stronghold\"&gt;Gnoll Stronghold&lt;/a&gt;. He will have five &lt;a href=\"hobgoblin\"&gt;hobgoblin&lt;/a&gt;s, hidden in the bushes at first, aiding him.\nPolite Banditry.\nUnlike most bandits, Neville is polite and well-spoken, whether he is pretending to be helpful or ordering your deaths.\nIf you demand that his party reveal themselves (dialogue option 1), or ask for his assistance (option 2), he and his party will attack. You will get 600 XP for killing Neville, another 175 XP for the hobgoblins, a &lt;a href=\"Long%20Sword%20%2B1\"&gt;Long Sword +1&lt;/a&gt;, a &lt;a href=\"Dispel%20Magic\"&gt;Dispel Magic&lt;/a&gt; scroll, a bandit scalp, and a few hundred worth of miscellaneous treasure.\nIf you try to turn the tables on him by demanding his money (dialogue option 3), your strategy will backfire. He will steal 55 from you and leave. You get 100 XP.\nDialogue.\n\"Ah, weary travelers, well met! Neville, the fairest of all fair bandits, at your service. What may I do for you this hour?\""}
{"id": "15708", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=15708", "title": "Nevin", "text": "Nevin is the ungrateful and resentful nephew of &lt;a href=\"Uncle%20Lester\"&gt;Uncle Lester&lt;/a&gt; encountered at the &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Graveyard\"&gt;Athkatla Graveyard&lt;/a&gt;.\nGameplay.\nWhen his uncle died, Nevin was given nothing but an old sweater that belonged to Lester. In response Nevin decided to cut corners by hiring the &lt;a href=\"Drunken%20Cleric%20of%20Talos\"&gt;Drunken Cleric of Talos&lt;/a&gt; to perform the funeral ceremony. However the funeral was not properly carried out and &lt;a href=\"Uncle%20Lester\"&gt;Uncle Lester&lt;/a&gt; has risen as a &lt;a href=\"zombie\"&gt;zombie&lt;/a&gt; to get revenge on his nephew.\nWhen first met Nevin will run to &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; to plea for help, but if saved from certain death, he will show no gratitude. Instead Nevin will complain of having to bury his uncle once more.\nWhile amusing to watch the scene (and the dialog) play out, waiting too long to deal with Uncle Lester after he attacks Nevin might result in Nevin's death. Allowing Uncle Lester to kill his nephew only nets &lt;a href=\"Random%20treasure%23Poor%20treasure\"&gt;poor random treasure&lt;/a&gt; from Nevin's corpse. Killing Uncle Lester grants . The party splits if they save Nevin from death, regardless of how ungrateful the \"git\" might still be."}
{"id": "37661", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=37661", "title": "New Ownership", "text": ""}
{"id": "37586", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=37586", "title": "Newer Kids on the Block", "text": ""}
{"id": "6988", "revid": "32294869", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=6988", "title": "Nexlit the Xvart", "text": "Nexlit the Xvart is the leader of the &lt;a href=\"xvart\"&gt;xvart&lt;/a&gt; village located in the &lt;a href=\"Area%20West%20of%20Nashkel\"&gt;Area West of Nashkel&lt;/a&gt;. He and the xvarts he leads are the ones responsible for the recent livestock raids in the &lt;a href=\"Nashkel\"&gt;Nashkel&lt;/a&gt; area. Appearance-wise, Nexlit is indistinguishable from a regular xvart.\nSummary.\nUpon entering the Xvart Village, Nexlit will approach &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; and party and accuse them of being monsters who kill xvarts indiscriminately, even when the xvarts have done nothing to merit such treatment. This accusation is, of course, false, as all xvarts the party encounters throughout the game are hostile and will attempt to kill the party on sight, with the exception of one group in the &lt;a href=\"Lonely%20Peaks\"&gt;Lonely Peaks&lt;/a&gt; that is too preoccupied with trying to kill &lt;a href=\"Hulrik\"&gt;Hulrik's&lt;/a&gt; cow first. \nNexlit's outrage does make a little more sense if the party stepped in, unprovoked, to defeat the Lonely Peaks raiding party prior to entering the village, especially considering the &lt;a href=\"Xvart%20Raids\"&gt;accompanying quest&lt;/a&gt; involves clearing out the village in order to stop the raids. However, Nexlit's reaction is the same whether Gorion's Ward has been to the Lonely Peaks or not. \nNexlit also gives Gorion's Ward no chance for a nonviolent confrontation. After his accusation, he, like all other xvarts, rushes in to attack. First, though, he calls upon the village's \"guardian\", &lt;a href=\"Ursa%20the%20Cave%20Bear\"&gt;Ursa the Cave Bear&lt;/a&gt;, to join the fight, claiming that she will protect him and the other villagers because she is kind. \nNote: Ursa, despite Nexlit's claims that she is a kind guardian, is a wild animal like any other, and as such, is just as likely to attack Nexlit and the other xvarts as she is to attack your party, so if you can arrange to get Nexlit between yourselves and Ursa before attacking, she may well become a (very temporary) ally.\nQuests.\n&lt;a href=\"Xvart%20Raids\"&gt;Xvart Raids&lt;/a&gt;.\nNexlit and the other inhabitants of the Xvart Village are the ones responsible for the recent livestock raids in the Nashkel area. Gorion's Ward first finds out about these raids when they encounter a farmer named &lt;a href=\"Hulrik\"&gt;Hulrik&lt;/a&gt; whose cow is under attack by a xvart raiding party, and is subsequently prompted to find and clear out the xvarts' base of operations. There are two such bases. Nexlit's little village is one of them, and defeating him is a part of the quest. The quest, however, is bugged, and the accompanying journal entry will not be cleared even after Gorion's Ward has successfully laid waste to the xvarts in both areas. "}
{"id": "5523", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5523", "title": "Niemain", "text": "Niemain is a mage who is found on the second floor of the &lt;a href=\"Sorcerous%20Sundries\"&gt;Sorcerous Sundries&lt;/a&gt; shop in &lt;a href=\"East%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;East Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;.\nWhen any member of the party goes upstairs in the Sorcerous Sundries, they will find Niemain and his companions practicing a spell, and he will hail you on sight and castigate you for having \"all but ruined\" his \"extremely difficult spell.\" If you don't apologize and leave immediately, Niemain and his three companion mages (&lt;a href=\"Oulam\"&gt;Oulam&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Wheber%20Ott\"&gt;Wheber Ott&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"William%20Garst\"&gt;William Garst&lt;/a&gt;) will attack, unless &lt;a href=\"Xzar\"&gt;Xzar&lt;/a&gt; and/or &lt;a href=\"Montaron\"&gt;Montaron&lt;/a&gt; are in the party. In that case, he will mention that Xzar has sent him reports about you and that you should investigate the &lt;a href=\"Iron%20Throne\"&gt;Iron Throne&lt;/a&gt; headquarters in the city. If Xzar is alive, you can ask him about Niemain and his group, and he will reveal that Niemain is a &lt;a href=\"Zhentarim\"&gt;Zhentarim&lt;/a&gt; and Xzar's superior.\nAs Niemain wears &lt;a href=\"The%20Jester%27s%20Folly\"&gt;The Jester's Folly&lt;/a&gt;, a cursed ring of clumsiness, he has -50% &lt;a href=\"Dexterity\"&gt;Dexterity&lt;/a&gt; and a 75% chance of spell failure during the battle, making him the least-threatening of the group \u2014 he will attempt to cast his repertoire of ten spells, then engage the party in melee combat with his &lt;a href=\"dagger\"&gt;dagger&lt;/a&gt;.\nNiemain is heavily implied to be the \"ill-humored mage in &lt;a href=\"Zhentil%20Keep\"&gt;Zhentil Keep&lt;/a&gt;\" that is mentioned in the ring's description."}
{"id": "15900", "revid": "49746547", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=15900", "title": "Night Club", "text": "Night Club (Night Club +1 in-game) is a unique Club +1 found in \"\", located in a chest in &lt;a href=\"Entar%20Silvershield\"&gt;Entar Silvershield&lt;/a&gt;'s garden in &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28city%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;. The Night Club possesses two unique qualities, the first being that it is treated as a +2 weapon for determining whether or not it can hurt enemies (no matter the time of day) and the second is that it grants its wielder an extra -1 bonus to THAC0 at night (so if this were to be used in the offhand, the mainhand weapon would also get that benefit and vice-versa).\nThe night time bonus to THAC0 works as an effect that lasts for 6 seconds that is cast on the character once every round (the 6\u2154-second definition of a round) as long as it is night time. Like many other \"do x every y seconds\" effects, this is affected by the &lt;a href=\"Haste%20effect\"&gt;haste&lt;/a&gt;: In this particular case, the bonus will be applied once every 3\u2153 seconds with the haste effect, allowing the character to receive a -2 bonus to THAC0 instead of the intended -1."}
