{"id": "4874", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4874", "title": "Non-Detection", "text": "Non-Detection renders the recipient protected from \"some\" divination spells.\nGameplay.\nThe caster may apply this spell onto single creature, including self, at a touch range.\nWhen the spell casting is finished the spell recipient is briefly covered in a lighting effect and color fade graphic, and a text is displayed reading \"Non-detected\".\nA player character spell recipient will show an icon (No. 31) titled \"Non-detectable\" on their portrait.\nWhen the spell is cast a sound effect is audibled, and another when the spell expires. \nThis spell protects an invisible or hidden (via Hide in Shadows/&lt;a href=\"Stealth\"&gt;Stealth&lt;/a&gt;) character from some low-level divination spells:\nIt does not protect against:\nGameplay note.\nBe aware that the &lt;a href=\"Whispers%20of%20Silence\"&gt;Whispers of Silence&lt;/a&gt; cloak provides a superior Non-Detection protection capability for certain users than the spell can provide.\nTrivia.\nThe Advanced Dungeons and Dragons 2nd Edition Wizard spell \"Non-Detection\" provides protection against the 2nd and 3rd level Priest and Wizard spells Clairaudience, Clairvoyance, Locate Object, and ESP. This protection also covers magical items such as a Crystal Ball or ESP medallion.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has changed this arcane spell, improving its effects and duration. See below for description:\nNon-Detection\nLevel: 3\nSchool: Abjuration\nRange: Touch\nDuration: 8 hours\nCasting Time: 3\nArea of Effect: 1 creature\nSaving Throw: None\nBy casting this spell, the wizard makes the creature touched undetectable by divination spells such as Detect Invisibility, Oracle, and True Seeing, or by a thief\u2019s Detect Illusion ability, though an invisible person may still be audible when moving and his presence may still be sensed. Non-Detection wards the creature\u2019s gear as well as the creature itself."}
