{"id": "50312", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=50312", "title": "Odendal Breachgnome", "text": "Odendal Breachgnome is a &lt;a href=\"Deep%20Gnome\"&gt;svirfneblin&lt;/a&gt; who lives in the &lt;a href=\"Underdark\"&gt;Underdark&lt;/a&gt; near the &lt;a href=\"drow\"&gt;drow&lt;/a&gt; city of &lt;a href=\"Ust%20Natha\"&gt;Ust Natha&lt;/a&gt;. He guards the deep gnome's mining settlement along with a few other sentries. He will hail your party when approached, and will initially speak in his own tongue, and not common.\nWhen you reach the Underdark in &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II%20Chapter%205\"&gt;Chapter 5&lt;/a&gt;, you will need to speak with Odendal in order to enter the Snirfneblin mining settlement. After you speak with him, he may allow you to enter peacefully. \nYour journal Entry will then display - \"I met the leader of the guards for a small village of svirfneblin. He advised that I may pass through as I wish, so long as I speak with their leader first.\" You should now enter the village, and speak with any deep gomes you meet, and especially &lt;a href=\"Goldander%20Blackenrock\"&gt;Goldander Blackenrock&lt;/a&gt;, the settlement leader. This is your key to progressing in the Underdark.\nMod content.\nPeople involved.\nInstallation of the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod makes a few changes to this creature. Dart weapon proficiency is now 5 pips, which will increase APR, weapon speed factor, THAC0 and damage. An SCS default script is added to improve tactical decision making and behavior. SCS random treasures are added to the inventory."}
{"id": "8203", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=8203", "title": "Odren", "text": "Odren is a fighter cleric priest of &lt;a href=\"Helm\"&gt;Helm&lt;/a&gt; and a &lt;a href=\"Knights%20of%20the%20Vigil\"&gt;Knight of the Vigil&lt;/a&gt;. He's found in a group of knights at the foot of &lt;a href=\"Watcher%27s%20Keep\"&gt;Watcher's Keep&lt;/a&gt;.\nGameplay.\nHe along with the other Knights of the Vigil had the task of keeping the &lt;a href=\"Demogorgon\"&gt;\"Imprisoned One\"&lt;/a&gt; sealed inside &lt;a href=\"Watcher%27s%20Keep\"&gt;Watcher's Keep&lt;/a&gt;. \nHe and the knights, not strong enough to complete the task, asked others for help - or more precisely &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt;.\nWhen you arrive at Watcher's Keep, Odren will be waiting below the looming structure. The player must initiate dialogue. Once dialogue is underway, at some point he'll ask you to perform a ritual to fortify the seals that hold the Imprisoned One beneath the keep. If the party agrees, the knights will then escort you to the top of the fortress (in a cutscene move).\nHis real intentions seem clear. But more about these may be presented later, if the party undertakes the quest.\nAlthough the game allows the player to attack Odren and the vigil knights at the first meeting and anytime afterwards, this action will result in the knight's defending themselves and shouting:\nThis action will have several plot altering repercussions on many variable scripts - the results of which aren't revealed to the player ahead of time. The gist of this action will be a shuttering and closure of several potential quest paths. In essence, the intended choices available to resolve this quest will be limited. Less overall experience points, roleplay options, rewards and gameplay will be the end result. Attacking the helmites provides no beneficial outcomes, and only less than ideal consequences. \nClearly, this is a less optimal path to take, so it isn't a recommended action. Additionally, several core Bioware companions will react negatively to this action. Mazzy (and others) may become hostile or leave the party forever. In the end, it's up to the player if they wish to go full-evil mode and exact revenge on the Helmites. But you'll have to live with the decision.\nIf the party ends up in combat with Odren he'll have access to both Cleric and some Druidic spells, as outlined in the InfoBox's scripted spell use.\nHe is also a competent level 20 fighter that dual wields enchanted maces. His THAC0 is good enough to strike a superior armor class.\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod makes some revisions to Odren. \nHe is provided with a new memorized repertoire of Divine spells (no Druid spells included now). A smarter Priest AI is assigned. His initial buffs include: &lt;a href=\"Blade%20Barrier\"&gt;Blade Barrier&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Armor%20of%20Faith\"&gt;Armor of Faith&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Magic%20Resistance%20%28spell%29\"&gt;Magic Resistance (spell)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spiritual%20Hammer\"&gt;Spiritual Hammer&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Fire%20%28priest%29\"&gt;Protection From Fire (priest)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Righteous%20Magic\"&gt;Righteous Magic&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Physical%20Mirror\"&gt;Physical Mirror&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Shield%20of%20the%20Archons\"&gt;Shield of the Archons&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Free%20Action%20%28spell%29\"&gt;Free Action (spell)&lt;/a&gt;.\nTwo ready to use potions are scripted for use to heal damage and enhance abilities.\nIf the &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod is installed, those spells will be the SR versions, such as &lt;a href=\"https%3A//gibberlings3.github.io/SpellRevisions/spells/divine/level-5/righteous-fury\"&gt;Righteous Fury&lt;/a&gt; instead of Righteous Might."}
{"id": "49466", "revid": "35642161", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49466", "title": "Of Elves and Artifacts", "text": "Of Elves and Artifacts is a tactical oriented quest mod, updated for the Baldur's Gate II: Enhanced Edition and the Baldur's Gate: Enhanced Edition Trilogy. The version for the original games was created by C. Bisson. The module was reworked and split out by Roxanne of the Baldur's Extended World website. This is a separated module from the Check the Bodies Mod (CtB), broken out from the mod to allow choices as what to add to your game from the original CtB.\nAfter your party has completed the adventures pertaining to Investigate the Deaths in the Umar Hills (Shade Lord quest in the hidden Temple), at some point in the Bridge District a cut scene will play and an elven woman will give you a small statuette. She escapes the scene before you can speak with her. Using the statuette will provide you with a plea for help and direct you to the Temple of Waukeen in Trademeet.\nFor more information see the link.\n&lt;a href=\"https%3A//github.com/RoxanneSHS/MalteseArtefact\"&gt;Mod Source&lt;/a&gt;"}
{"id": "30202", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=30202", "title": "Of Simulacrum and Sanity", "text": ""}
{"id": "7952", "revid": "773742", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=7952", "title": "Offensive Spin", "text": "Offensive Spin is an ability unique to &lt;a href=\"Blade\"&gt;Blade&lt;/a&gt;s that increases their mobility and damage output for a short duration.\nEffects.\nThe extra &lt;a href=\"Game%20Terminology%23A\"&gt;attack per round&lt;/a&gt; is granted through a &lt;a href=\"Haste%20effect\"&gt;normal Haste effect&lt;/a&gt; in the . In &lt;a href=\"Enhanced%20Edition\"&gt;Enhanced Edition&lt;/a&gt; no haste is applied, but the Blade gains a straight +1 APR and movement rate is set to 200% instead.\nEnhanced Editions also try to prevent stacking Haste effects with the Spin. Upon being cast, it removes all effects from &lt;a href=\"Oil%20of%20Speed\"&gt;Oil of Speed&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a href=\"Haste\"&gt;Haste spell&lt;/a&gt;, whether it came from an &lt;a href=\"Arcane%20Magic\"&gt;arcane&lt;/a&gt; spellcaster or a &lt;a href=\"Stalker%23Priest%20Spellbook\"&gt;Stalker&lt;/a&gt;. It then prevents any Haste effect from being (re-)applied for as long as it is active.\nAlso, activating Offensive Spin again while it is active, does not stack, it merely extends the duration."}
{"id": "50579", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=50579", "title": "Offensive damage type", "text": "Offensive damage is a secondary spell type, a characteristic of spells, abilities and weapon on-hit side effects. While secondary types are hidden from the player, some of them can be leveraged to better attack or defend. When it comes to the offensive damage type, there is only one way to target it: The &lt;a href=\"Cloak%20of%20Mirroring\"&gt;Cloak of Mirroring&lt;/a&gt;. It grants immunity to all attacks of this type unless they were cast by the wearer.\nList of offensive damage attacks.\nDespite the name, not all attacks that deal damage have this secondary type, and some attacks have it that deal no damage. The list below is quite thorough:\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod make changes to Dragon Breath weapon attacks and ensure the breath spell school is \"Generalist Mage\" and \"Secondary Type\" is \"None\". This means that they are not offensive damage, or magical attack types any longer with these mods installed. &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Immunity\"&gt;Spell Immunity&lt;/a&gt; and items that guard against secondary type classifications have no effect on Dragon Breath attacks. Other examples may include &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Shield\"&gt;Spell Shield&lt;/a&gt; or the &lt;a href=\"Cloak%20of%20Mirroring\"&gt;Cloak of Mirroring&lt;/a&gt;.\nDemilich howl also has no secondary type assigned with those mods."}
{"id": "13552", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=13552", "title": "Officer Dirth", "text": "Officer Dirth is an member of the Amnian Military who is found standing near the end of the bar, puffing a pipe and sipping a pint inside the &lt;a href=\"Sea%27s%20Bounty%20Tavern\"&gt;Sea's Bounty Tavern&lt;/a&gt;. He will have nothing to offer in the way of meaningful dialogue until you have undertaken the &lt;a href=\"Nalia%20abducted%20by%20Isaea%20Roenall\"&gt;Nalia abducted by Isaea Roenall&lt;/a&gt; companion quest.\nOnce the quest is begun and the party has spoken with the pirate &lt;a href=\"Barg\"&gt;Barg&lt;/a&gt;, Officer Dirth will now have a few more conversation paths to explore on his dialogue tree. He'll acknowledge that he knows &lt;a href=\"Isaea%20Roenall\"&gt;Isaea Roenall&lt;/a&gt; and, if &lt;a href=\"Free%20Hendak%20and%20the%20slaves\"&gt;Hendak and the slaves&lt;/a&gt; were freed and &lt;a href=\"Captain%20Haegan\"&gt;Captain Haegan&lt;/a&gt; killed, Dirth will mention this as well. Calling him a slaver will also raise his hackles. All of these actions result in Dirth becoming hostile and attacking the party.\nKilling Officer Dirth and looting the corpse will reveal that he is in possession of &lt;a href=\"Isaea%27s%20Slavery%20Document\"&gt;Isaea's Slavery Document&lt;/a&gt;, one of the proofs needed to incriminate Isaea."}
{"id": "41810", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=41810", "title": "Officer Jenks", "text": "When you visit the &lt;a href=\"Flaming%20Fist%20Headquarters\"&gt;Flaming Fist Headquarters&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Chapter%207\"&gt;Chapter 7&lt;/a&gt; of &lt;a href=\"Siege%20of%20Dragonspear\"&gt;Siege of Dragonspear&lt;/a&gt; , Officer Jenks can be addressed as one of the officers on duty in the main barracks of the compound.\nQuests.\n&lt;a href=\"Rabble-Rousers\"&gt;Rabble-Rousers&lt;/a&gt;.\n&lt;a href=\"Officer%20Vida\"&gt;Officer Vida&lt;/a&gt; , stationed near the &lt;a href=\"Elfsong%20Tavern\"&gt;Elfsong Tavern&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Sorcerous%20Sundries\"&gt;Sorcerous Sundries&lt;/a&gt; is finding herself overwhelmed by the flood of refugees whilst trying to maintain order. She will ask the player to assist by visiting the Flaming Fist Headquarters on her behalf and asking Officer Jenks for reinforcements."}
{"id": "5518", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5518", "title": "Officer Vai", "text": "Officer Jessa Vai is a &lt;a href=\"Flaming%20Fist\"&gt;Flaming Fist&lt;/a&gt; officer who appears in &lt;a href=\"Chapter%20Three\"&gt;Chapter Three&lt;/a&gt; inside the &lt;a href=\"Jovial%20Juggler\"&gt;Jovial Juggler&lt;/a&gt;.\nWhen the player enters &lt;a href=\"Beregost\"&gt;Beregost&lt;/a&gt; at any time during chapter three, a young girl named &lt;a href=\"Chloe\"&gt;Chloe&lt;/a&gt; will approach you upon sight near the northeast corner of the inn and &lt;a href=\"Officer%20Vai%20%28quest%29\"&gt;tell you&lt;/a&gt; that Vai is looking to meet with you. (She'll be there even if you've already spoken with Vai) \nWhen you enter the Jovial Juggler, Vai will immediately introduce herself. She laments that &lt;a href=\"bandit\"&gt;bandit&lt;/a&gt;s in the area have cut off the roads to her &lt;a href=\"Flaming%20Fist%20HQ\"&gt;headquarters&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28city%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt; and asks you to sort out the bandit problem. From that point on, she offers to buy any &lt;a href=\"Bandit%20Scalp\"&gt;Bandit Scalp&lt;/a&gt; from the party for each. You must have at least one Bandit Scalp in inventory to open the Buy/Sell screen, and Officer Vai will say:\"You have been busy, I see. Well, keep at it. The more bandit scalps I have, the richer you'll be. I'll take all the bandit scalps you have.\"After the player has cleared out the &lt;a href=\"Bandit%20Camp\"&gt;Bandit Camp&lt;/a&gt; and advanced to &lt;a href=\"Chapter%20Four\"&gt;Chapter Four&lt;/a&gt;, Officer Vai will leave if spoken to without at least one bandit scalp in the player's inventory. This will raise your reputation by one and also flags the completion of the &lt;a href=\"Kivan%20and%20Tazok\"&gt;Kivan and Tazok&lt;/a&gt; companion quest, making &lt;a href=\"Kivan\"&gt;Kivan&lt;/a&gt; a potential permanent party member. In parting, Officer Vai says:\"Thank you,\" Gorion's Ward\". You\" [sic] \"efforts have not been in vain. I just received new orders from the city: my contingent and I have been asked to return there and make our reports. You will figure prominently in them and I assure you that our accounts will be favorable.\""}
{"id": "9968", "revid": "46775035", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=9968", "title": "Officer Vai (quest)", "text": "This quest begins in &lt;a href=\"Chapter%20Three\"&gt;Chapter Three&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Beregost\"&gt;Beregost&lt;/a&gt; when &lt;a href=\"Chloe\"&gt;Chloe&lt;/a&gt; runs up to you with a message to meet &lt;a href=\"Officer%20Vai\"&gt;Officer Vai&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Jovial%20Juggler\"&gt;Jovial Juggler&lt;/a&gt;. It is completed after talking to Vai about bounties on bandits."}
{"id": "7470", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=7470", "title": "Oghma", "text": "Oghma, also known as the Binder of What is Known or the Patron of Bards, is a &lt;a href=\"true%20neutral\"&gt;true neutral&lt;/a&gt; greater &lt;a href=\"deity\"&gt;deity&lt;/a&gt; of knowledge and invention.\nHe is the most powerful god of knowledge in the realms and is often depicted as a man in fine, bright clothing. It is said that he decides on whether a new idea will be made known to the world or if it will stay confined to its originator."}
{"id": "11006", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=11006", "title": "Ogre", "text": "An ogre is a large, brutish creature that can be found in many places around the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast\"&gt;Sword Coast&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Amn\"&gt;Amn&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Tethyr\"&gt;Tethyr&lt;/a&gt;.\nNotable ogres.\nThese may be named ogres, or only referred to \"Ogre\" in-game but unique nevertheless, sometimes involving quests:\nTrivia.\nThe offical website for the original game, now archived, had \u2013 in addition to some combat-related statistics \u2013 the following information about these :\"Ogres are big, ugly, greedy humanoids that live by ambushes, raids, and theft. Ill tempered and nasty, these monsters are often found serving as mercenaries in the ranks of &lt;a href=\"orc\"&gt;orc&lt;/a&gt; tribes, &lt;a href=\"Alignment\"&gt;evil&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"cleric\"&gt;cleric&lt;/a&gt;s, or &lt;a href=\"gnoll\"&gt;gnoll&lt;/a&gt;s. They mingle freely with &lt;a href=\"giant\"&gt;giant&lt;/a&gt;s and &lt;a href=\"troll\"&gt;troll&lt;/a&gt;s.Adult ogres stand 9 to 10 feet tall and weigh 300 to 350 pounds. Their skin colors range from a dead yellow to a dull black-brown, and (rarely) a sickly violet. Their warty bumps are often of a different color - or at least darker than their hides. Their eyes are purple with white pupils. Teeth and talons are orange or black. Ogres have long, greasy hair of blackish-blue to dull dark green. Their odor is repellent, reminiscent of curdled milk. Dressing in poorly cured furs and animal hides, they care for their and &lt;a href=\"armor\"&gt;armor&lt;/a&gt; only reasonably well.\""}
