{"id": "52060", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=52060", "title": "Ogre (Mind Flayer Jailer)", "text": "Ogre (Mind Flayer Jailer) is a speaking NPC that interacts with the party in the &lt;a href=\"Mind%20Flayers%20in%20Underdark\"&gt;Mind Flayers in Underdark&lt;/a&gt; area.\nGameplay.\nShortly after the entering the Mind Flayers in the Underdark complex, a cut scene animation indicates that the Illithids have been able to overcome the mental faculties of the party.\nThe player's group awakens in a locked cell chamber. Eventually, this Ogre opens the cell door and communicates with the party, informing them of their unfortunate situation.\nThere is an opportunity to ask this Ogre, who is in some kind of Jailer role (he might be a slave or servant of the mind flayers). The Ogre will first reply:\nThe party finds out that they will be forced to fight for the amusement of the Illithids. The Ogre was once in the same predicament, but survived and was rewarded or promoted to the current job as a servant.\nThe Mind Flayers within are extra powerful due to the presence of \"real big brain\"\".\nThe party will have to face an arena style battle of various creatures, then placed back in the cell (with a few freely provided healing potions). An adjacent cell finds a number of Githyanki creatures, including &lt;a href=\"Simyaz\"&gt;Simyaz&lt;/a&gt; their leader. Through dialogue and collaboration, a plan is hatched to allow an escape attempt with the Gith's help.\nDuring another arena battle including the party versus the Githyanki, they facilitate a chance for the party to escape from the arena - with the Gith occupying the illithids in some strange psychic battle of wills. Only one door can be opened, and the party will come face to face with the Ogre again, who now has nothing to say and attacks.\nThe Ogre has no melee weapon and just starts beating on the closest person it can detect. The Ogre must have some kind of psionic protection in this place, as it is extraordinarily tougher than an ordinary ogre. If defeated, no items are found on the jailer.\nMod content.\nInstallation of the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; only provides a new default AI script for improved tactical behavior for a warrior/ogre style creature."}
{"id": "11007", "revid": "46775035", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=11007", "title": "Ogre Berserker", "text": "Ogre Berserkers are tougher versions of &lt;a href=\"ogre\"&gt;ogre&lt;/a&gt;s that can be found in many places in &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt; and , often alongside their weaker kind. Unlike normal, green-skinned ogres, berserkers have lavender or grey skin.\nSummons.\nOgre Berserkers can be summoned by the spell &lt;a href=\"Monster%20Summoning%20III\"&gt;Monster Summoning III&lt;/a&gt; except in the original edition of BG1. Summoned versions have a higher constitution (and therefore more hit points), but a slightly lower intelligence, and higher saving throws. They only attack once per round at an increased THAC0.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; revises the summoned Ogre Berserker. It is now a 7th level fighter class with a Berserker Kit, with 88 HP. It may use it's &lt;a href=\"Enrage\"&gt;Enrage&lt;/a&gt; ability once. It uses the OGREGRSU.ITM weapon, which has a range of 1 and speed of 3. It deals 1d10 +3 crushing damage and has a +2 THAC0 bonus. It is classified as a +1 enchanted item. This creature has an adjusted THAC0 of 5. It will strike twice per round. Its final adjusted damage per hit will be 1d10 +12 crushing damage, which is devastating in BGEE, and still good in BG2EE. If under its Enrage innate ability, it will hit more frequently and inflict even more damage, so beware, or rejoice if it is your ally."}
{"id": "6975", "revid": "773742", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=6975", "title": "Ogre Hunting", "text": "Ogre Hunting is a quest that you get from\u00a0\n&lt;a href=\"Sarhedra\"&gt;Sarhedra&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0in the &lt;a href=\"Lonely%20Peaks\"&gt;Lonely Peaks&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0area north of &lt;a href=\"Carnival\"&gt;Carnival&lt;/a&gt; (&lt;a href=\"coordinates\"&gt;coordinates&lt;/a&gt; 4760, 1750). She wants you to kill some &lt;a href=\"Ogre\"&gt;Ogre&lt;/a&gt;s\u00a0to the south. You will find 2 Ogres, 1 Ogrillon, 1 Ogre Berserker and 2 Hobgoblin Elite archers, beginning at about\u00a04560, 2650. You can fight them in two groups of 3 if you don't rush in.\nWhile you're in the neighborhood, loot the corpse at 4390, 2750 for a &lt;a href=\"Potion%20of%20Healing\"&gt;Potion of Healing&lt;/a&gt; , a cursed &lt;a href=\"Oil%20of%20Speed\"&gt;Oil of Speed&lt;/a&gt; and 59 gp.\nReturn to Sarhedra for 300 xp."}
{"id": "11058", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=11058", "title": "Ogre Mage", "text": "Ogre Mages are a more intelligent and more dangerous variant of &lt;a href=\"ogre\"&gt;ogre&lt;/a&gt;s. Capable of casting various spells, they are a potent foe in combat and will likely be difficult for low-level parties to overcome, though they pose little to no threat to parties at higher levels. They are found in all of the games although some of their stats may be changed.\nVariants.\nOgre Mages appear as &lt;a href=\"Enemies\"&gt;enemies&lt;/a&gt; in all of the games, although some start out in a neutral stance as they have dialogue to run through before turning hostile. Some appear as named creatures and a couple of these creatures are tough opponents if encountered early in the game (see notable ogre mages below).\nIt appears from the game files that an ogre mage may be summoned as an ally in the , but this needs verification.\nGameplay.\nMost Ogre Mages are under level 6 and so vulnerable to &lt;a href=\"Command\"&gt;Command&lt;/a&gt;.\nThey all have well developed spellbooks and will utilize every spell in battle. Most of them come equipped with a &lt;a href=\"Bastard%20Sword\"&gt;Bastard Sword&lt;/a&gt; which they use in melee combat once their spells are depleted, although the weapon isn't dropped upon death and can't be pickpocketed. A couple of ogre mages use &lt;a href=\"Katana\"&gt;Katana&lt;/a&gt;s, instead of bastard swords, which are dropped upon death. Those ogre mages that are equipped with a bastard sword as a weapon will instead drop from their inventory either a &lt;a href=\"Scimitar\"&gt;Scimitar&lt;/a&gt; or different bastard sword . Most of them also drop between three to four items of &lt;a href=\"Random%20treasure%23RNDTRE05\"&gt;rich random treasure&lt;/a&gt; while a few will drop no treasure at all.\nMany of them also wear an undroppable/unstealable &lt;a href=\"MAGE01.ITM\"&gt;Sandthief's Ring&lt;/a&gt; which is triggered anytime an area where they are located is entered. Some mages will also utilize the ring before every spell casting attempt.\nThe InfoBox to the right lists all of those stats which mostly remain unchanged for all ogre mage creatures found throughout all of the games."}
{"id": "47288", "revid": "272312", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=47288", "title": "Ogre Mage (Baldur's Gate I)", "text": "Ogre Mages are found throughout &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt; and appear as intended enemies, in the &lt;a href=\"Firewine%20Ruins\"&gt;Firewine Ruins&lt;/a&gt; for example, as well as a possible random encounter enemy in the &lt;a href=\"Lonely%20Peaks\"&gt;Lonely Peaks&lt;/a&gt; or during &lt;a href=\"Random%20Encounter%20%28BG%29\"&gt;travels&lt;/a&gt; between certain areas. Two stand alone NPC's - &lt;a href=\"Droth\"&gt;Droth&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Kahrk\"&gt;Kahrk&lt;/a&gt; - are a couple of formidable ogre mage enemies that may be encountered while exploring the map.\nOgre Mages (except Kahrk) are under level 6 and so especially vulnerable to the spell &lt;a href=\"Command\"&gt;Command&lt;/a&gt;.\nAll of the mages share a majority of the same combat and protection stats (the sewer mage has a few differences). They mainly differ in the makeup of their spellbook, their race script, and whether or not they possess a undroppable/unstealable &lt;a href=\"Sandthief%27s%20Ring\"&gt;Sandthief's Ring&lt;/a&gt;. Most of them are also equipped with an undroppable/unstealable &lt;a href=\"Bastard%20Sword\"&gt;Bastard Sword&lt;/a&gt; which is used during melee combat. All of them will also drop three items of &lt;a href=\"Random%20treasure%23RNDTRE05\"&gt;rich random treasure&lt;/a&gt; except for the sewer mage which drops treasure that is specific only to itself.\nAll of the following ogre mages are categorized by their creature code for ease of discussion.\nOGREMA02 / OGREMA03.\nThese ogre mages can be encountered as early as &lt;a href=\"Chapter%20One\"&gt;Chapter One&lt;/a&gt; (in the Firewine Ruins - OGREMA02) and during the events of &lt;a href=\"Chapter%20Four\"&gt;Chapter Four&lt;/a&gt; (on the third level of the &lt;a href=\"Cloakwood%20Mine%20level%203\"&gt;Cloakwood Mine&lt;/a&gt; - OGREMA03). They both have an allegiance of neutral as they will initiate dialogue before becoming hostile.\nOGREMA.\nThis ogre mage creature file is used as one of five ogre mages found in a &lt;a href=\"Generic%20homes%20%28south%20Baldur%27s%20Gate%29%23AR1201\"&gt;generic home&lt;/a&gt; located in &lt;a href=\"South%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;South Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt; as well as the a potential random spawn enemy in the Lonely Peaks area and during travels between mainly southern areas of the map.\nOGREMA_A-D.\nThese four ogre mages comprise the remaining mages that are found in the &lt;a href=\"Generic%20homes%20%28south%20Baldur%27s%20Gate%29%23AR1201\"&gt;generic home&lt;/a&gt; located in &lt;a href=\"South%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;South Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;. While they all maintain the same combat and defensive stats (OGREMA_D starts out with Neutral allegiance due to dialogue), their spellbooks all contain between 1 to 3 unique spells that aren't found in the other mages spellbook.\nGameplay.\n\"Spell Casting:\".\nThe ogre mages will cast the following spells (\"race script\".bcs):\n\u039b\nOGRMBA.\nThis ogre mage is the creature found in the &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20Sewers%20East\"&gt;east sewers&lt;/a&gt; located under the city of &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28city%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;. It has the weakest stats of any ogre mage found throughout the &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;game&lt;/a&gt; as its &lt;a href=\"Hit%20point\"&gt;Hit point&lt;/a&gt;s, &lt;a href=\"strength\"&gt;strength&lt;/a&gt;, number of attacks, and its &lt;a href=\"THAC0\"&gt;THAC0&lt;/a&gt; have all been reduced. It's also one of three ogre mages (&lt;a href=\"Droth\"&gt;Droth&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Kahrk\"&gt;Kahrk&lt;/a&gt; being the other two) in the game that has &lt;a href=\"humanoid\"&gt;humanoid&lt;/a&gt; instead of as its type and is assigned male instead of neither as its gender."}
{"id": "47296", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=47296", "title": "Ogre Mage (Shadows of Amn)", "text": ""}
{"id": "47289", "revid": "53053884", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=47289", "title": "Ogre Mage (Siege of Dragonspear)", "text": "The Ogre Mages found in are the only ogre mages that are multi-classed as &lt;a href=\"Fighter%20/%20Mage\"&gt;fighter/mage's&lt;/a&gt;. As a result, they also have had their &lt;a href=\"dexterity\"&gt;dexterity&lt;/a&gt; increased to account for the fighter aspect of the class. They only use a &lt;a href=\"katana\"&gt;katana&lt;/a&gt; during melee combat and none of them are even equipped with a &lt;a href=\"bastard%20sword\"&gt;bastard sword&lt;/a&gt;. They're given two &lt;a href=\"weapon%20proficiency\"&gt;weapon proficiency&lt;/a&gt; bonus slots for katana and &lt;a href=\"Weapon%20Proficiency\"&gt;single-weapon style&lt;/a&gt;. This is the only game were none of the mages are equipped with the undroppable/unstealable &lt;a href=\"Sandthief%27s%20Ring\"&gt;Sandthief's Ring&lt;/a&gt;.\nBoth of the following ogre mages are categorized by their creature code for ease of discussion.\nbdogre03.\nThis ogre mage is encountered in the &lt;a href=\"Troll%20Claw%20Woods\"&gt;Troll Claw Woods&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Chapter%20Nine%20%E2%80%93%20Boareskyr%20Bridge\"&gt;chapter nine&lt;/a&gt; and in &lt;a href=\"Dead%20Man%27s%20Pass\"&gt;Dead Man's Pass&lt;/a&gt; during &lt;a href=\"Chapter%20Ten%20%E2%80%93%20Allied%20Siege%20Camp\"&gt;chapter ten&lt;/a&gt;. It is one of the few ogre mages assigned male as its gender and is the only \"generic\" ogre mage to be given a kit classification ().\nIt also has double digit scores across all six abilities and has the highest total ability score (92) of any ogre mage found in all of the games. And it is the only ogre mage that possess an undroppable/unstealable &lt;a href=\"Ring%20of%20Regeneration\"&gt;Ring of Regeneration&lt;/a&gt;.\nbdwave16.\nTwo of these ogre mages are encountered among the first wave of enemy crusaders that attacks the &lt;a href=\"Coalition%20Camp\"&gt;Allied Siege Camp&lt;/a&gt; during the three attempts by the Coalition to destroy the camp in &lt;a href=\"Chapter%20Ten%20%E2%80%93%20Allied%20Siege%20Camp\"&gt;chapter ten&lt;/a&gt;. Both this ogre mage and the &lt;a href=\"Ogre%20Mage%20%28Shadows%20of%20Amn%29%23Umar%20Hills%20%28Paladin%20Stronghold%20quest%29\"&gt;paladin stronghold ogre mage&lt;/a&gt; in are given the highest level (7/8 and 8 respectively) of any ogre mage . This ogre mage also has the highest XP value (1400) of any generic ogre mage in the series."}
