{"id": "2473", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2473", "title": "Algernon", "text": "Algernon is a tubby guest who can be found in an expensive room on the second floor of &lt;a href=\"Feldepost%27s%20Inn\"&gt;Feldepost's Inn&lt;/a&gt; in the town of &lt;a href=\"Beregost\"&gt;Beregost&lt;/a&gt;. He is the owner of a &lt;a href=\"Algernon%27s%20Cloak\"&gt;nymph cloak&lt;/a&gt;, which can be pick-pocketed from him or collected from his corpse, should he be killed.\nOne method to try in obtaining the cloak is you can use &lt;a href=\"Charm%20Person\"&gt;Charm&lt;/a&gt; spells on Algernon and summon a creature, then direct him to attack your summons, and watch the summons do the dirty deed without the hit to reputation! (Note: not all summons react to friendly attack)\nSide quests.\n&lt;a href=\"Pheirkas\"&gt;Pheirkas&lt;/a&gt; desires to possess Algernon's Cloak, and she hires &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; and party to 'acquire' it for her while leaving Algernon alive."}
{"id": "2470", "revid": "53053884", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2470", "title": "Algernon's Cloak", "text": "This intricate cloak belongs to &lt;a href=\"Algernon\"&gt;Algernon&lt;/a&gt;, currently residing at &lt;a href=\"Feldepost%27s%20Inn\"&gt;Feldepost's Inn&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Beregost\"&gt;Beregost&lt;/a&gt;.\u00a0It offers a +2 &lt;a href=\"Charisma\"&gt;Charisma&lt;/a&gt; bonus to the wearer and the ability to cast Charm Creature once per day.\nLocation.\nThough obtainable already long before &lt;a href=\"Chapter%20Five\"&gt;Chapter Five&lt;/a&gt; of \"&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;\" by &lt;a href=\"pickpocket\"&gt;pickpocket&lt;/a&gt;ing (or slaying) &lt;a href=\"Algernon\"&gt;Algernon&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Beregost\"&gt;Beregost&lt;/a&gt;'s &lt;a href=\"Feldepost%27s%20Inn\"&gt;Feldepost's Inn&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Pheirkas\"&gt;Pheirkas&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Northwest%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;northwestern&lt;/a&gt; district of the &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28city%29\"&gt;city of Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Steal%20Algernon%27s%20Cloak\"&gt;asks&lt;/a&gt; for this . Slaying Algernon will result in a loss of Reputation.\nGameplay.\nAlgernon's Cloak variant of \"Charm Creature\":"}
{"id": "48866", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=48866", "title": "Alhelor", "text": "Alhelor is a human &lt;a href=\"mage\"&gt;mage&lt;/a&gt; and a member of the retribution squad from the &lt;a href=\"Most%20Noble%20Order%20of%20the%20Radiant%20Heart\"&gt;Most Noble Order of the Radiant Heart&lt;/a&gt; that has been sent to administer justice upon the party for the killing of five knights in the &lt;a href=\"Windspear%20Hills\"&gt;Windspear Hills&lt;/a&gt; area during the &lt;a href=\"Journey%20to%20the%20Windspear%20Hills\"&gt;Journey to the Windspear Hills&lt;/a&gt; side quest. The squad is composed of three &lt;a href=\"paladin\"&gt;paladin&lt;/a&gt;s, a &lt;a href=\"cleric\"&gt;cleric&lt;/a&gt;, a &lt;a href=\"fighter/cleric\"&gt;fighter/cleric&lt;/a&gt;, and the mage.\nThey will randomly appear in the &lt;a href=\"Bridge%20District\"&gt;Bridge&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Docks\"&gt;Docks&lt;/a&gt;, or the &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Slums\"&gt;Slums&lt;/a&gt; districts, or &lt;a href=\"Waukeen%27s%20Promenade\"&gt;Waukeen's Promenade&lt;/a&gt; at any time of the day or night to attack the party for the party's horrific act of murder. All of this can be avoided if the party takes up &lt;a href=\"Garren%20Windspear\"&gt;Garren Windspear&lt;/a&gt;'s offer of temporary sanctuary inside his &lt;a href=\"Windspear%20Cabin\"&gt;cabin&lt;/a&gt; following the battle with the knights. After some conversation inside the cabin, Windspear will set off to try to clear the party's name with the Radiant Heart by contacting some of his former friends within the Order. A task in which he is ultimately successful in accomplishing.\nThere is a second reason why the party may encounter the Radiant Heart enforcer group (including Alhelor) in Athkatla - and that occurs if the party's reputation falls to the \"Despised\" ranking.\nThe Radiant Heart enforcers group will attack the party on sight, with little or no warning. See the Gallery further below.\nMod content.\nWith the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod installed, and especially with the \"Smarter Mage\" component, this mage will be assigned a kit (Invoker, Enchanter, Conjurer or Necromancer - randomly determined upon install). The mage will have prepared \"Previously Cast\" initial buffs, prepared sequencers and Spell Trigger. On Hardcore and Insane difficulty will utilize mage &lt;a href=\"High-level%20class%20ability\"&gt;High-level class ability&lt;/a&gt;. A different spell book will be provided than the unmodded game - and whichever kit is present will influence the scripted memorized spells for use. \nExpect a &lt;a href=\"Time%20Stop\"&gt;Time Stop&lt;/a&gt; with at least two spells cast during that pause in time. An SCS random potion is provided for quaffing to the mage. This mage will be more difficult to face than the regular game version by a noticeable degree, with considerable staying power."}
{"id": "27217", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=27217", "title": "Alhoon", "text": "An Alhoon is a unique undead &lt;a href=\"Mind%20Flayer\"&gt;Mind Flayer&lt;/a&gt;. The term is used to describe all outcasts from mind flayer societies who had defied the ruling Elder Brains to achieve a limited form of lichdom. Only the most powerful mind flayer mages could achieve true lichdom and were known as illithiliches.\nAlhoons combined powerful wizardry and sorcery with their innate &lt;a href=\"Psionic%20Ability\"&gt;Psionic Ability&lt;/a&gt;. The lore about the Alhoon strongly suggests that they are formidable foes, however, the in-game version is configured to be well below those expectations and more akin to a Ulitharid who can get up a few protection spell buffs, but only once. So, fear not if you are a new player - they aren't really much tougher than a standard mind flayer.\nGameplay.\nThe Alhoon's covered on this page share the same AI scripting, and mostly will perform in identical fashion. There may be different combat log displays that are triggered and or inserted by the specific Area scripts the creatures appear in.\nWhen the creature is alerted to an enemy, it will apply &lt;a href=\"Stoneskin\"&gt;Stoneskin&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Mirror%20Image\"&gt;Mirror Image&lt;/a&gt; on self (uninteruuptible).\nThe next action will be to launch a &lt;a href=\"Psionic%20Blast\"&gt;Psionic Blast&lt;/a&gt;, which has a moderate Area of Effect and can expose party members clustered together to the potential &lt;a href=\"Stun\"&gt;Stun&lt;/a&gt; effect.\nIf the creature manages to survive a few more rounds it will attempt a &lt;a href=\"Psionic%20Domination\"&gt;Psionic Domination&lt;/a&gt; at the nearest target.\nIf one of its nearby opponents is damaged below 25% of original HP, the Alhoon will try and cast a &lt;a href=\"Maze\"&gt;Maze&lt;/a&gt; arcane spell at it.\nThis creature can use its tentacle tendrils and attack in melee combat like any illithid, causing minor crushing damage and a \"Devour Brain\" effect, temporarily draining 5 &lt;a href=\"Intelligence\"&gt;Intelligence&lt;/a&gt;.\nThis creature can't assess an opponent's protections and immunities and won't know if a target is immune to charm or stun. It can however tell if a target is already affected by stun, and that will alter its behavior slightly in battle.\nIn the unmodified game, the Alhoon won't be able to survive a party onslaught very long and has limited staying power. The creature isn't provided with the 100% elemental resistances that a standard Mind Flayer has, which may be an oversight, as it is supposed to be some sort of lich. Even normal weapons can strike it as well.\nMod Content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod revitalizes the theme that the Alhoon is a powerful illthid creature with a potent spell casting ability. In basic terms the mod designs the creature as a lich in many respects, but with the psionic powers of a Ulitharid. If the player installs the \"Smarter Mind Flayers\" component, then the Alhoon will be at its peak potential.\nOn Hardcore and above difficulty settings the Alhoon will get additional 50% physical damage resistance (due to its alien physiology and psionics). In addition, the creature now is equipped with the &lt;a href=\"LICH.ITM\"&gt;LICH.ITM&lt;/a&gt; which gives the Alhoon the same immunities as a standard &lt;a href=\"Lich\"&gt;Lich&lt;/a&gt;. It can also &lt;a href=\"See%20the%20invisible\"&gt;See the invisible&lt;/a&gt; and is under a permanent &lt;a href=\"Improved%20Alacrity\"&gt;Improved Alacrity&lt;/a&gt; power.\nThe creature has been revised to a level 20 caster and an improved &lt;a href=\"THACO\"&gt;THACO&lt;/a&gt; of 3, and with the SCS \"Smarter Mage\" component is scripted to select spells to cast from an entire spell book repertoire, and on the higher game difficulty setting will also have mage &lt;a href=\"High-level%20class%20ability\"&gt;High-level class ability&lt;/a&gt; choices. Prepared &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Sequencer\"&gt;Minor Sequencer&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Sequencer\"&gt;Spell Sequencer&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Trigger\"&gt;Spell Trigger&lt;/a&gt; are ready to use as well.\nExpect several reactionary castings of protective spells to remain immune to magical weapons. The script knows when a spell has expired or been dispelled/breached and will renew it.\nThe Alhoon will summon help to include twin &lt;a href=\"Mordenkainen%27s%20Sword\"&gt;Mordenkainen's Sword&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Efreeti\"&gt;Efreeti&lt;/a&gt; allies, and one of its HLA's is a gated &lt;a href=\"Dark%20Planetar\"&gt;Dark Planetar&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe creature can also launch any of the innate illithid abilities discussed on the &lt;a href=\"Psionic%20Ability\"&gt;Psionic Ability&lt;/a&gt; article, sometimes in the same round as a spell cast. It's &lt;a href=\"Psionic%20Blast\"&gt;Psionic Blast&lt;/a&gt; is the more potent Ulitharid version with a -4 saving throw penalty.\nIf the party flees the room or closes the door - then the Alhoon and any remaining illithids with it may \"Planar Travel\" across the map to the party's \"rear' areas - no one is entirely safe from being followed anywhere on the map. Because psionics.\nIf the &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod is installed, the Alhoon's spell choices will be the SR version.\nIf the SCS Icewind Dale spell component is installed, or the &lt;a href=\"IWDification\"&gt;IWDification&lt;/a&gt; mod, then some spells will be those versions.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Golem%20Construction%20for%20Spellcasters\"&gt;Golem Construction for Spellcasters&lt;/a&gt; mod adds a bodyguard &lt;a href=\"Brain%20Golem\"&gt;Brain Golem&lt;/a&gt; to this Alhoon's lair as well."}
{"id": "15132", "revid": "40332393", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=15132", "title": "Alianna", "text": "Alianna was a priestess of &lt;a href=\"Bhaal\"&gt;Bhaal&lt;/a&gt;, the &lt;a href=\"protagonist\"&gt;protagonist's&lt;/a&gt; mother and allegedly &lt;a href=\"Gorion\"&gt;Gorion's&lt;/a&gt; friend and 'occasional lover'. Her race changes depending on which race the protagonist has.\nBaldur's Gate: Siege of Dragonspear.\nIn the &lt;a href=\"Ruined%20Temple%20of%20Bhaal\"&gt;Ruined Temple of Bhaal&lt;/a&gt;, now dedicated to &lt;a href=\"Cyric\"&gt;Cyric&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Madele\"&gt;Madele&lt;/a&gt; confirms that Gorion and Alianna were lovers. Gorion attempted to reform Alianna, believing his love could change her. Madele says that \"passion led him to careless speech, and she brought his words back to the temple,\" implying that Alianna may have seduced him to gather information on the Harpers. Gorion begged Alianna not to sacrifice her own child to Bhaal before one of Gorion's allies shot her in the throat with an arrow.\nBaldur's Gate II: Throne of Bhaal.\nAlianna appears as a ghost in the &lt;a href=\"Pocket%20Plane\"&gt;Pocket Plane&lt;/a&gt;, alongside the ghost of Gorion, after the player kills &lt;a href=\"Yaga-Shura\"&gt;Yaga-Shura&lt;/a&gt;. She reveals her true identity as a priestess of Bhaal, how she came to be the mother of a &lt;a href=\"Bhaalspawn\"&gt;Bhaalspawn&lt;/a&gt; and how Gorion killed her.\nThis means that Gorion lied in the &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Note\"&gt;letter&lt;/a&gt; the player finds in the first game, where he stated that she died in childbirth.\nPossible Plot-Hole.\nEither the information given is a lie or it creates a plot-hole. Her statement implies that she was still alive during the &lt;a href=\"Time%20of%20Troubles\"&gt;Time of Troubles&lt;/a&gt; and that she gave birth and died around the same time. That would mean the protagonist is just about ten years old during the time the games take place, which they are clearly not."}
{"id": "13323", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=13323", "title": "Alibakkar Estate", "text": "The Alibakkar Estate is a noble mansion in &lt;a href=\"Trademeet\"&gt;Trademeet&lt;/a&gt; in \"\". It belongs to the Alibakkar family, one of the most powerful in this town. Current leader is Lord Skaramaen Alibakkar."}
{"id": "49034", "revid": "773742", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49034", "title": "Alibakkar Guard", "text": "An Alibakkar Guard is one who is dedicated to House Alibakkar under the leadership of &lt;a href=\"Lord%20Skarmaen%20Alibakkar\"&gt;Lord Skarmaen Alibakkar&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Trademeet\"&gt;Trademeet&lt;/a&gt; during the campaign.\nThere are four varieties (i.e., creature files) of guard, but they all have a few things in common. The are all Human Male &lt;a href=\"Fighter\"&gt;Fighters&lt;/a&gt; of Lawful Neutral &lt;a href=\"Alignment\"&gt;Alignment&lt;/a&gt;.\nMost of these guards (creature codes codice_1, codice_2, and codice_3) are protected by &lt;a href=\"Basic%20Helmets%20%28Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II%29\"&gt;Open-Faced Helmets&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Plate%20Mail\"&gt;Plate Mail&lt;/a&gt;. Their active weapon is a &lt;a href=\"Longbow\"&gt;Longbow&lt;/a&gt; for ranged attacks with mundane &lt;a href=\"Arrow\"&gt;Arrows&lt;/a&gt; . They may also close to melee with &lt;a href=\"Two-handed%20Sword\"&gt;Two-Handed Swords&lt;/a&gt;. They carry and are worth each.\nA fourth type (codice_4) is of 3rd level, equipped with only &lt;a href=\"Studded%20Leather%20Armor\"&gt;Studded Leather Armor&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Bastard%20Sword\"&gt;Bastard Sword&lt;/a&gt;. He is worth , but carries no gold.\nAll guards are Neutral unless hostilities ensue.\nRelated Quests.\n&lt;a href=\"The%20Dueling%20Families%20of%20Trademeet\"&gt;The Dueling Families of Trademeet&lt;/a&gt;"}
{"id": "3124", "revid": "36603496", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=3124", "title": "Alignment", "text": "In \"&lt;a href=\"w%3Ac%3Aforgottenrealms%3ADungeons%20%26amp%3B%20Dragons\"&gt;Dungeons &amp; Dragons&lt;/a&gt;\", all beings from the &lt;a href=\"w%3Ac%3AForgottenrealms%3APrime%20Material%20plane\"&gt;Prime Material plane&lt;/a&gt; \u2014 where most of the \"Baldur's Gate\" series takes place \u2014 have an alignment that represents and simplifies their morality and inner stance with regard to rules. Their morality is simplified down to being good, neutral or evil, while their stance toward rules boils down to being lawful, neutral or chaotic. Alignment is somewhat helpful for a person playing the tabletop RPG to stay \"in character\", but it also has a tangible reality that fictional characters themselves can leverage to gain information about others, using spells like &lt;a href=\"Know%20Alignment%20%28wizard%29\"&gt;Know Alignment&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Detect%20Evil%20%28wizard%29\"&gt;Detect Evil&lt;/a&gt;.\nBeyond the Prime Material plane, however, beings exist that represent the spiritual embodiment of an alignment, and planes that bend people and even physics to fit one alignment. For example in the plane that embodies chaos of the purest kind, &lt;a href=\"w%3Ac%3Aforgottenrealms%3ALimbo\"&gt;Limbo&lt;/a&gt;, even beings that embody pure law may become corrupted over time, and the laws of physics themselves are abolished. In the planes, alignment shapes reality, not the other way around \u2014 entire cities may shift and change plane if the alignments of its inhabitants start to collectively lean too strongly toward it. Things are not so drastic in the Prime Material plane, where the mind has a much smaller impact on hard rock.\nConcretely, alignment represents all combinations of these two axes of three values, meaning a total of nine possible alignments. The law-chaos axis is always expressed before the good-evil axis. A \"Neutral good\" character has a neutral stance as far as rules are concerned, but seeks to do good. In the \"Baldur's Gate\" series, alignment is used in gameplay to disallow equipping certain items, open or close certain dialogue paths, affect &lt;a href=\"Companions\"&gt;companion&lt;/a&gt; reaction to the party's &lt;a href=\"reputation\"&gt;reputation&lt;/a&gt;, adapt the effects of a few spells, and other minor things.\nLawful Good.\nLawful Good is known as the \"Saintly\" or \"Crusader\" alignment. A Lawful Good character typically acts with compassion, and always with honor and a sense of duty. A Lawful Good nation would consist of a well-organized government that works for the benefit of its citizens. Lawful Good characters include righteous knights, paladins, and most dwarves. Lawful Good creatures include the noble golden dragons. Lawful Good outsiders are known as Archons.\nLawful Good characters, especially &lt;a href=\"paladin\"&gt;paladin&lt;/a&gt;s, may sometimes find themselves faced with the dilemma of whether to obey the law or good when the two conflict\u2014for example, upholding a sworn oath when it would lead innocents to come to harm\u2014or conflicts between two orders, such as between their religious law and the law of the local ruler.\n&lt;a href=\"%23ex\"&gt;Examples from the \"Complete Scoundrel\"&lt;/a&gt;: , and are cited as being lawful good characters.\nNeutral Good.\nNeutral Good is known as the \"Benefactor\" alignment. A Neutral Good character is guided by his or her conscience and typically acts altruistically, without regard for or against Lawful precepts such as rules or tradition. A Neutral Good character has no problems with co-operating with lawful officials, but does not feel beholden to them. In the event that doing the right thing requires the bending or breaking of rules, they do not suffer the same inner conflict that a Lawful Good character would.\n&lt;a href=\"%23ex\"&gt;Examples&lt;/a&gt; of Neutral Good characters include and . The Neutral Good outsiders are known as &lt;a href=\"w%3Ac%3Aforgottenrealms%3AGuardinal\"&gt;Guardinals&lt;/a&gt;.\nChaotic Good.\nChaotic Good is known as the \"Beatific,\" \"Rebel,\" or \"Cynic\" alignment. A Chaotic Good character favors change for a greater good, disdains bureaucratic organizations that get in the way of social improvement, and places a high value on personal freedom, not only for oneself, but for others as well. They always intend to do the right thing, but their methods are generally disorganized and often out of alignment with the rest of society. They may create conflict in a team if they feel they are being pushed around, and often view extensive organization and planning as pointless, preferring to improvise.\n and are &lt;a href=\"%23ex\"&gt;examples&lt;/a&gt; of Chaotic Good individuals. &lt;a href=\"w%3Ac%3Aforgottenrealms%3ACelestial%20eladrin\"&gt;Eladrin&lt;/a&gt; are the outsider race representing Chaotic Good.\nLawful Neutral.\nThe game manual takes this text from the \"Player's Handbook\" of AD&amp;D 2, but adds one sentence and changes one of the two examples given. The differences with the original text are outlined below:\n, , and are &lt;a href=\"%23ex\"&gt;considered&lt;/a&gt; as Lawful Neutral. Three exemplars of Lawful Neutral outsiders exist: the &lt;a href=\"w%3Ac%3Aforgottenrealms%3AFormian\"&gt;Formians&lt;/a&gt;, the Inevitables and the &lt;a href=\"w%3Ac%3Aforgottenrealms%3AModron\"&gt;Modrons&lt;/a&gt;.\nTrue Neutral.\nThe game manual takes this text from the \"Player's Handbook\" of AD&amp;D 2, but removes a few sentences and shortens others. See the relevant parts from the original text below:\n&lt;a href=\"Animals\"&gt;Animals&lt;/a&gt; and constructs such as &lt;a href=\"golems\"&gt;golems&lt;/a&gt; are all true neutral, but only as a way to express an absence of choice regarding concepts such as good and evil or law and chaos.\n&lt;a href=\"%23ex\"&gt;Examples&lt;/a&gt;: , and are neutral. The true neutral outsiders are known as the Rilmani.\nChaotic Neutral.\nThe AD&amp;D 2 \"Player's Handbook\" uses this exact description, but extends it with the following:\n, and are Chaotic Neutral characters, according to the \"&lt;a href=\"%23ex\"&gt;Complete Scoundrel&lt;/a&gt;\". The chaotic outsiders are known as the &lt;a href=\"https%3A//forgottenrealms.fandom.com/wiki/Slaad\"&gt;Slaadi&lt;/a&gt; (other than the Death Slaadi).\nLawful Evil.\nThe game manual takes this text from the \"Player's Handbook\" of AD&amp;D 2, but removes a few sentences, shortens others, and adds a bit about pride of power. See the relevant parts from the original text below:\n and are cited &lt;a href=\"%23ex\"&gt;examples&lt;/a&gt; of Lawful Evil characters. The Lawful Evil outsiders are known as &lt;a href=\"w%3Ac%3Aforgottenrealms%3ABaatezu\"&gt;Baatezu&lt;/a&gt; (devils).\nNeutral Evil.\nThe AD&amp;D 2 \"Player's Handbook\" uses this exact description, but contains some additional sentences:\n\"&lt;a href=\"%23ex\"&gt;Complete Scoundrel&lt;/a&gt;\" cites and as Neutral Evil characters. &lt;a href=\"w%3Ac%3Aforgottenrealms%3AYugoloth\"&gt;Yugoloths&lt;/a&gt; (daemons) are the outsiders of Neutral Evil.\nChaotic Evil.\nThe AD&amp;D 2 \"Player's Handbook\" uses this exact description, but contains some additional sentences:\nChaotic evil outsiders are known as the &lt;a href=\"Tanar%27ri\"&gt;Tanar'ri&lt;/a&gt; (demons), a race of beings constantly at war with the baatezu. \nAlignment and class.\nAlignment is chosen at &lt;a href=\"character%20generation\"&gt;character generation&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0and restricted by\u00a0&lt;a href=\"class\"&gt;class&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0kit. For &lt;a href=\"human\"&gt;human&lt;/a&gt;s, this makes it a consideration towards &lt;a href=\"dual-class\"&gt;dual-class&lt;/a&gt; possibilities. In addition to the &lt;a href=\"ability%20score\"&gt;ability score&lt;/a&gt; requirements, the character must have a compatible alignment to be able to dual into a particular class.\nNo wizard kit has any alignment restrictions, though alignment does have a minor effect on their &lt;a href=\"High-level%20class%20ability\"&gt;High-level class ability&lt;/a&gt; selection. &lt;a href=\"Summon%20Planetar\"&gt;Summon Planetar&lt;/a&gt; is for good wizards, while &lt;a href=\"Summon%20Dark%20Planetar\"&gt;Summon Dark Planetar&lt;/a&gt; is for evil wizards. Those of neutral morality can choose one or the other, but not both.\nAlignment for clerics and paladins.\nAll &lt;a href=\"paladin\"&gt;paladin&lt;/a&gt;s must be lawful good, with the exception of &lt;a href=\"blackguard\"&gt;blackguard&lt;/a&gt;s, who can have any evil alignment. The base &lt;a href=\"cleric\"&gt;cleric&lt;/a&gt; class has no alignment restrictions, but all of its kits do:\nFor kitless clerics, alignment will determine which &lt;a href=\"Cleric%23Class_exclusive_items\"&gt;holy symbol&lt;/a&gt; will be obtained upon reaching level 25. For &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt;, it also determines the &lt;a href=\"Cleric%20Stronghold\"&gt;Cleric Stronghold&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe moral alignment of a cleric or paladin will determine the effects of &lt;a href=\"Turn%20Undead\"&gt;Turn Undead&lt;/a&gt;. Evil ones can start taking control of undead monsters with this ability as they level, while those of other alignments will instantly destroy them. Moral alignment will also affect their spell selection: &lt;a href=\"Holy%20Smite\"&gt;Holy Smite&lt;/a&gt;,\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Holy%20Word\"&gt;Holy Word&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0and &lt;a href=\"Summon%20Deva\"&gt;Summon Deva&lt;/a&gt; cannot be cast by evil clerics or blackguards, while &lt;a href=\"Unholy%20Blight\"&gt;Unholy Blight&lt;/a&gt;,\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Unholy%20Word\"&gt;Unholy Word&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0and &lt;a href=\"Summon%20Fallen%20Deva\"&gt;Summon Fallen Deva&lt;/a&gt; are barred from good clerics and paladins. Neutral clerics can cast all the spells.\nAlignment for Gorion's Ward.\nIn \"&lt;a href=\"Throne%20of%20Bhaal\"&gt;Throne of Bhaal&lt;/a&gt;\", the alignment of &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; will affect the first two &lt;a href=\"Pocket%20Plane%20%28area%29\"&gt;Pocket Plane&lt;/a&gt; challenges. The following table displays the starting &lt;a href=\"Reputation\"&gt;Reputation&lt;/a&gt; when beginning a new game in any campaign and after exporting the character file to \"&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II\"&gt;Baldur's Gate II&lt;/a&gt;\". It also shows which creature will appear if the protagonist casts\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Find%20Familiar\"&gt;Find Familiar&lt;/a&gt;.\nCompanions' alignment.\n\"See also: .\"\nIn the first game, the &lt;a href=\"paladin\"&gt;paladin&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Ajantis\"&gt;Ajantis&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0may eventually start fights against any evil &lt;a href=\"companions\"&gt;companions&lt;/a&gt; in the party with him. Across the series, companions' &lt;a href=\"reputation\"&gt;reputation&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0tolerance ranges are determined by their moral alignment.\nEquipment.\nSome items restrict the alignment of the user by excluding certain alignment combinations. This can result in multiple alignment combinations being restricted as follows:\nRogues with the &lt;a href=\"High-level%20class%20ability\"&gt;High-level class ability&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Use%20Any%20Item\"&gt;Use Any Item&lt;/a&gt; can ignore these restrictions.\nAlignment changes.\nIn the first game, equipping the &lt;a href=\"Helm%20of%20Opposite%20Alignment\"&gt;Helm of Opposite Alignment&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0is the only way to change anybody's alignment. In \"&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II\"&gt;Baldur's Gate II&lt;/a&gt;\", certain characters can have alignment changes based on choices made."}
